<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UPS and Teamsters Agree to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Parcel Service
(UPS) and the Teamster's union announced today a tentative
agreement to end the 15-day strike after five days of talks.
</P>
<P>
"We realize that our customers have suffered many
inconveniences, and I want to assure them that our great service
is going to be available to them very soon," UPS chief negotiator
David Murray said at an early morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
The settlement ended a strike that idled 185,000 workers and
most operations of the nation's largest package carrier.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed Monday to a five-year deal that includes
the creation of 10,000 new full-time jobs from existing part-time
positions. UPS also will raise pay for full-time workers by 3.10
dollars an hour over the life of the contract and keep a
multi-employer pension plan.
</P>
<P>
An average full-time driver for UPS was previously paid 19.95
U.S. dollars an hour.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said the agreement was
significant for the whole country because it takes historic steps
toward providing health and retirement benefits for part-time
workers.
</P>
<P>
About 58 percent of UPS jobs are filled by part-time workers,
and their 8 dollar an hour base salary has not increased since
1982. Under the agreement, their starting wage would increase by
50 cents an hour.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, who is vacationing outside Washington,
praised the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Teamsters, who account for nearly two-thirds of the 302,000
UPS employees in the United States, went on strike August 4,
causing UPS an estimated 300 million dollars in losses each week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
