<HEADLINE> Regional Weather Experts to Discuss Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Southern African weather experts
will meet next month in Zimbabwe to discuss prospects for the
next rainy season in the region, Zimbabwe's Meteorological Office
Director Marufu Zinyowera said today.
</P>
<P>
The director said, ''we in southern Africa have decided that
we need to look at the prospects of a drought in the region and
see what we can come up with as a prediction of the coming
season.''
</P>
<P>
He said, ''met officers from southern africa will meet from
September 8 to 12 in Kadoma where we will look at all the
scientific data available and come up with our own predictions
for the next season.''
</P>
<P>
''When we leave we will have a reasoned position on the coming
rainy season which we will review from time to time on a 10-day
basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) regional
Early Warning Unit said in its July report that global climatic
trends pointed to a possibility of poor rains in the region
during the 1997/98 crop season.
</P>
<P>
The unit said events were following a trend frequently
associated with dry years.
</P>
<P>
''Although it is still early to make any definite predictions
concerning the next rainy season... observations of global
climatic data and results of climate forecasting models point to
the possibility of another warm El Nino-Southern Oscillation
(ENSO) occurring during the 1997/98 crop growing season,'' the
unit said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
