<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 More Tajik Rebels Surrender to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 19 (Xinhua) -- About 200 troops loyal to
Tajikistan's renegade Colonel Makhmud Khudoiberdyev have
surrendered to the government, the Interfax news agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The rebels surrendered their weapons in the Kabodien and
Shaartuz regions in southern Tajikistan. The rebels have not been
punished and they have the choice of either demobilising or
continuing military service in government units, the report quoted
Tajik Deputy Defense Minister Abdullo Khabibov as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said the surrender followed an earlier one of 500
troops from Khudoiberdyev's force, which originally was reported
to be numbered at 1,500.
</P>
<P>
According to information, about 50 rebels were killed during
the last two days of fighting with government troops in southern
Tajikistan, while the number of wounded remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
Khabibov said the government troop's major task at present is
to seek out Khudoiberdyev, who is reportedly trying to escape to
the Uzbek border with 60-70 supporters.
</P>
<P>
An armed confrontation between Khudoiberdyev's supporters and
Uzbek border guards took place on Monday night near the Uzbek
village of Sangou.
</P>
<P>
The deputy defense minister ruled out the possibility of
Khudoiberdyev's having escaped to Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
"The Uzbek and Tajik governments have reached a firm agreement
on not allowing rebels to be in the territory of a neighboring
country. In an extreme case, they will be disarmed and handed
over to the Tajik government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan's current military conflict first occurred on August
9 between the supporters of Sukhrob Kasymov, commander of a
special-purpose brigade of the Tajik Interior Ministry, and those
of Customs Committee Chairman Yakub Salimov.
</P>
<P>
The situation deteriorated when Khudoiberdyev, commander of a
presidential rapid reaction brigade was involved in the conflict
in an effort to support the units of Salimov.
</P>
<P>
Khudoiberdyev reached a peace agreement with the government
earlier last week but fighting was soon renewed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
