<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record VAT Revenue Cuts Government Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The British government's spending
swung into surplus last month, after an unexpectedly large payment
of VAT receipts.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury reported that July's total of just over 8 billion
US dollars in VAT revenue was the largest monthly cash figure on
record. In the same period last year, VAT receipts were 6.08
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The surge was helped by changes to the timing of VAT payments,
which have enabled large companies to pay VAT in the first month
of each quarter. Previously, payment were more spread out.
</P>
<P>
Michael Saunders, a UK economist at Salomon Brothers, said:
"VAT receipts in April were 42% up year-on-year, down in May and
June, and 33% higher in July.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise in revenue also points to stronger economic
activity, in line with the projections in July's Budget. In the
financial year to date VAT revenue was up 7.2% on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The news appeared to give support to the government's forecast,
put forward at the general election, that it will need to borrow
just 17.44 billion US dollars, or less, this year to satisfy
spending plans.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of the financial year, the net public
sector borrowing requirement (PSBR) is just 7.04 billion US
dollars down from 12.96 billion US dollars in the third quarter of
1996-97. The June PSBR has been revised down by 320 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Simon Briscoe, a UK economist at Nikko Europe, said: "These are
fundamentally good numbers and the improvement we are seeing as
the months go by confirm that this Budget forecast is easily
achievable."
</P>
<P>
The Office of National Statistics yesterday reported that the
PSBR in June had been revised from 7.68 billion US dollars to 7.36
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The PSBR for the whole of the last financial year was 36.16
billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
