<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR: Situation Remains Tense in Banja Luka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Stablization Force (SFOR)
led by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) said today it
has increased troop presence in Banja Luka due to the tense
situation in the Serb city.
</P>
<P>
The action was taken after 100 civilians gathered outside the
Banja Luka police headquarters last night before police had a
chance to set up checkpoints, said SFOR spokesman Major John
Blakeley.
</P>
<P>
The crowd later dispersed and the checkpoints were either
dismantled by SFOR troops or by the police themselves, according
to SFOR.
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation this morning in Banja Luka as "tense,"
Blakeley said "we have an increased presence of troops and we are
taking precautions we deem necessary to ensure the situation
remain stable."
</P>
<P>
The police headquarters in Banja Luka saw a potential clash
between policemen loyal to Republika Srpska President Biljana
Plavsic and those controlled by her political opponents in Pale.
</P>
<P>
In a pre-dawn raid on Sunday, elements of the sixth battalion
of the Serb special police loyal to Plavsic took over the building
to search for bugging devices they claimed had been used by
civilian police to spy on Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
SFOR later turned down a request from Pale to use other special
police to take back the police station. They intervened by
escorting the special police back to their barracks and returned
the building to the civilian police.
</P>
<P>
Blakeley said that because the action by the sixth battalion of
Serb police violated Dayton accords on military movement, SFOR
confiscated some of its weapons and banned its activities, except
for providing protection to VIPs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
