<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Cultural Exchanges Urged in Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior Mozambican government
official today said unity and economic ties between southern
African countries can be enhanced through the promotion of
cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Culture Director Carlos Jorge Silia said during the ongoing
Linkfest arts festival in Bulawayo, the country's second largest
city that such exchanges provided an opportunity for the
countries to relate to each other's needs along cultural
barometers.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''the SADC (Southern African Development Community)
music festival held in Harare in 1995 enabled people in the
region to see their cultural differences and similarities for the
first time.''
</P>
<P>
''This consolidated our African identity, cooperation among
the states, as well as acknowledgement of each other's
differences in ways of living,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed it is not true that African culture is facing
extinction under massive influence from the western culture being
promoted among youths.
</P>
<P>
The threat, he said, could only come if the older generation
fails to educate the youths about the African heritage which has to
be passed on to future generations.
</P>
<P>
He described the recent SADC theater festival held in his
country's capital city, Maputo, as a huge success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
