<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1630 GMT, August 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United Parcel Service (UPS) and the
Teamster's union announced today a tentative agreement to end the
15-day strike after five days of talks.
</P>
<P>
"We realize that our customers have suffered many
inconveniences, and I want to assure them that our great service
is going to be available to them very soon," UPS chief negotiator
David Murray said at an early morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
The settlement ended a strike that idled 185,000 workers and
most operations of the nation's largest package carrier.
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodian government forces claimed today they
had captured the town of O'Smach, the last major stronghold held
by loyalists of Prince Norodom Ranariddh. But the prince and his
followers denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of the Cambodian Royal Army Ke Kimyan
said in Phnom Penh that the town fell to government forces at
about 1:00 p.m. (0600 GMT) today.
</P>
<P>
Casualties of both sides were still unknown, he said.
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- A ground-breaking ceremony was held today in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), marking the start of
a landmark nuclear reactor construction project which was agreed
upon by the DPRK and the U.S. in Geneva in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony began at 14:00 local time as scheduled at Kumbo in
the DPRK's eastern coastal province of South Hamkyong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
