<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Ruling Party Stresses Law on Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenyan African
National Union (KANU)'s 122 parliamental members reiterated today
that all constitutional reform talks between KANU and the
Opposition must be kept within the existing legislative frame.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully committed to dialogue and consultation within
the existing constitutional and legal framework," said KANU chief
J. Kamotho in a statement on behalf of KANU lawmakers who enjoy a
big majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
"All dialogue and consultations must always be cognizant of
the existing constitutional structures and procedures" with
religious leaders as "impartial" mediators, he said after a
meeting of the KANU parliamental group.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was chaired by President Daniel arap Moi, one day
before the expected reform talks reportedly to be held tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
However, KANU Secretary General Kamotho refused to confirm the
talks, saying it still depends on concerned consultations this
afternoon. But a report from the Kenyan News Agency said today
that KANU has decided on a 37-member negotiation team.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kamotho said the KANU government will not succumb
to pressure to postpone the general elections set for 1997 until
the constitution reforms are undertaken.
</P>
<P>
"Hurried constitutional reformulations, especially in the
current changed political atmosphere of the general election eve,
can easily end up resulting in provisions designed... to satisfy
short term interests," he warned.
</P>
<P>
He also charged the opposition umbrella body National
Convention Assembly (NCEC), which claimed last Thursday the
formation of a 50-member team for talks, has always intended to
cause chaos by calling illegal mass actions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he denied any involvement of KANU with a nearly
week-long bloodshed violence in the region around the coastal
city of Mombasa where more than 30 people, including nine
policemen, were killed.
</P>
<P>
The KANU parliamental group "condemned the perpetrators of the
violence and called upon the national law enforcement agencies to
bring them to book and... do everything possible to restore peace
and tranquillity in the area," said Kamotho.
</P>
<P>
The KANU lawmakers' meeting came at a time when the political
temperature was being simmered as the east African country gears
for the general elections whose date is yet to be fixed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
