<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Starts Unchanged Last Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Housing starts in the U.S.
were unchanged in July although the mortgage rates declined in the
month, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the housing starts in July were at a
1.45 million seasonally adjusted annual rate.
</P>
<P>
But it revised the originally estimated 4.8 percent increase in
June down to just 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Single-family starts, which account for about 80 percent of the
total, increased by 2.7 percent to a 1.14 million annual rate. It
was the second straight advance.
</P>
<P>
But construction of apartments and condominiums fell by 8.9
percent to a 306,000 rate, nearly erasing a 10.5 percent gain a
month earlier.
</P>
<P>
So far in 1997, U.S. housing starts totaled 3.1 percent less
than they did during the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, the starts soared by 41.4 percent in the Northeast.
But they were down by 5.3 percent in the West, 3.7 percent in the
Midwest and 2.4 percent in the South.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 7.43
percent in July, down from 7.69 percent a month earlier. However,
the rates increased to 7.54 percent last week, highest since 7.62
percent in early July.
</P>
<P>
Applications for building permits, often a barometer of future
activity in the country, rose 1.4 percent in July to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.42 million compared with 1.4 million in
June.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts expected construction in the U.S. would level off
this year while continuing at a healthy pace after the housing
starts had reached an eight-year high of 1.48 million last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
