<HEADLINE> Mongolia, China Sign Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen signed here today with his
Mongolian counterpart Shukher Altangerel a treaty of extradition
after the two ministers vowed to further develop bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that Mongolian and Chinese peoples enjoy a
traditional friendship, and exchanges and cooperation between the
two countries in the fields of politics, economy, culture and
education have made great progress since they normalized bilateral
relations in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Qian also spoke highly of Mongolia's China policy, which he
said was in keeping with the interests of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
As for economic relations, Qian said the economy of the two
countries complement each other and they should, on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit, explore new ways to further expand
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Mongolia is committed to forming a good-neighborly
relationship with China, Altangerel hoped the two countries would
also expand economic cooperation and trade ties. He said Mongolia
was rich in mineral resources and would be happy to cooperate with
China and other countries in exploring these resources.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here today for a four-day official visit,
held talks earlier with Mongolian Prime Minister Mendsaikhan
Enkhsaikhan. Both expressed the hope during the talks to further
develop friendship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
