<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private, Public Sectors' Partnership Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- President of Zimbabwean National
Chamber of Commerce Danny Meyer today urged partnerships between
the private and public sectors for economic prosperity in a
concept dubbed "Team Zimbabwe".
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon hosted by the Chartered Institute of
Secretaries, Meyer said economic development in the country was
being hindered by various aspects being turned "political".
</P>
<P>
"It has taken us all a long time to realize that "team
zimbabwe" is the way forward, and to remove the them-and-us
culture which has developed and existed for decades between the
public and private sectors," said Meyer.
</P>
<P>
The private and public sectors, he said, should work for a
common goal to make Zimbabwe and the region succeed economically
and socially.
</P>
<P>
Important issues such as accelerated participation by black
Zimbabweans, creating an enterprise culture, increasing
unemployment, non-availability of funding for projects at
affordable and realistic interest rates, a national industrial
policy have been turned into "political" ones which have much
talk with no action.
</P>
<P>
"We all dearly love our country and we want it to succeed.
Team Zimbabwe is the only way forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meyer chronicled failures or disappointments on the part of
the government, which he said included a failure in reviewing the
educational system to modify it in order to contribute more
positively toward creating an enterprise culture in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The other failures included the continued absence of a
national productivity center, the slow pace or length of time it
had taken to establish a permanent private-public sector
consultative body and the tariff commission, as well as removal
of laws or by-laws which retarded business development or stifled
entrepreneurial initiatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
