<HEADLINE> Bruin Wins Her First Gold Since Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's Michelle de Bruin took
her first gold in the 400-meter individual medley Tuesday in the
European Swimming Championships held in Sellive of Spain since she
won three gold medals in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin, 27, clocked four minutes 42.08 seconds, the best time
in Europe this season and the third best time in the world, though
she had no qualifying time in this event.
</P>
<P>
Yana Klochkova of Ukraine was second in 4:43.07 and Hana Cerna
of the Czech Republic was third in 4:44.05.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin won the 200 and 400 individual medley and 400
freestyle in Atlanta last year but seldom raced after that.
</P>
<P>
In other races, German Sandra Voelker finished first in the
100-meter women's freestyle final, clocking 55.38 seconds. Martina
Moravcova of Slovakia was second with a time of 55.46 and German
Antje Buschschulte third with 55.50.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100-meter breaststroke final, Bulgarian Alexander
Goukov won the gold in 1:02.17, followed by Hungarian Karoly
Guttler in 1:02.23 and Danie Malek of the Czech Republic in
1:02.27.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Jens Kruppa, who holds the fastest time of 1:01.91 in
Europe this season, finished seventh in 1:02.72.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Paul Palmer beat all the other rivals to won in the
men's 200-meter freestyle with 1:48.85, while the silver went to
Italian Massimiliano Rosolino in 1:49.02 and bronze to Bela
Szabados of Hungary in 1:49.98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
