<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Help Farmers with Water Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Vice-President Simon
Muzenda today said water and irrigation and the implementation of
an appropriate land policy are key issues critical to the
commercialization of small-holder agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the 58th annual congress of the Zimbabwe
Farmers Union, Muzenda said the government has now committed
itself to building dams to enable farmers to derive more benefits
from water resources for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
"My government has initiated a medium-size dam construction
program that will cover all provinces," he said.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda said the distribution of seed and fertilizer packs
throughout the country, which was started in 1992, would be
extended again this year.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government is receiving assistance through a
non-governmental organization, Care International, in
implementing an "agro-dealer program" aimed at developing the
capacity of local entrepreneurs to source, store and distribute
inputs to the small-holder farmers.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the rate of growth in small-holder farm output
for food and cash crops had been low in recent years resulting in
many farmers unable to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
"Admittedly, the problem has been partly due to resource and
climatic constraints," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
