<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Intelligence Head Denounces Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Army intelligence
head Moshe Yaalon today denounced Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat for not giving up violence and terrorism as means to reap
political gains.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a security briefing to the Knesset (Parliament)
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee, Yaalon said that there was
only slight progress in stepping up the cooperation between
Israeli and Palestinian security forces despite the recent thaw in
security relations.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon claimed that the moves taken by the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) in resuming security cooperation with
Israel was only aimed at pleasing the United States ahead of the
pending visit of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was very keen on Albright's first visit to the region
because he believed that this would lead to the calming of the
tense situation, and the PNA could take advantage of this
opportunity to stress the economic hardship caused by Israel's
sanctions taken following the July 30 Mahane Yehuda market
bombings in Jerusalem, the general added.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon believed that the twin bombings, which killed 16 people
and wounded 170 others, were carried out by the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas), an anti-Israeli militant group, as it had
claimed. But he still could not rule out the possibility that the
two suicide bombers were from abroad as the PNA has insisted.
</P>
<P>
The intelligence chief also charged that Arafat was trying to
unite all Palestinian opposition groups in an attempt to
strengthen the capability to sponsor what was called "spontaneous
violence" against Israel. He criticized Arafat for refusing to
crack down on terrorism and their infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, Palestinian officials were quoted by Israel
Radio as condemning Yaalon for his consistent anti-Palestinian
attitude. They noted that this was not the first time for Yaalon
to try to damage the relations between the PNA and Israel's
General Security Service (GSS).
</P>
<P>
Yaalon's accusation came only after a secret meeting held
Monday night between GSS head Ami Ayalon and Arafat, during which
Ayalon thanked Arafat for his cooperation in investigating the
Mahane Yehuda bombings and in apprehending three Palestinian
killers of an Israeli taxi driver last Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Arafat renewed his call for Israel to
lift totally the sanctions on the Palestinian people, including
a total closure on the territories and the continued freeze on
most of tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
Despite the exchange of charges, Israeli, Palestinian and
U.S. representatives conducted joint investigations today into
the Jerusalem bombings. They detonated some explosives uncovered
by the Palestinian police from a Hamas bomb factory near
Bethlehem to determine whether they were the same explosives
used in the twin bombings.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security experts said that the explosion showed
that there was no connection between the explosives, indicating
once again that the suicide bombers were not from the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Israeli Finance Ministry today
informed its PNA counterpart that Israel had transferred 4.2
million dollars of the tax revenues to the PNA. The money, which
was deposited into the PNA account in an Israeli bank, was part
of the total 14 million dollars withheld by Israel following the
Mahane Yehuda bombings.
</P>
<P>
Israel announced Monday to partially release the frozen money
as a reward for the partial security cooperation provided by the
Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh said that Israel
was still demanding the PNA to take tougher measures against
terror organizations and their infrastructure, and Israel's
further easing of the sanctions depends on the PNA's actions on
this issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Wants U.N. to Adopt Measures on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government wants to
see the U.N. adopting measures to ensure the implementation of its
resolutions on the Cyprus issue, a Cypriot government spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Manolis Christofides
stressed that it is the time for the U.N. to examine all available
ways to promote the implementation of their resolutions on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Cyprus expects the U.N. and the Security Council
to "present an objective picture" of the direct talks already held
between President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Special Advisor to the U.N. Secretary-General Diego Cordovez,
who chaired the two rounds of direct talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides, will present his report on the talks to the
Security Council on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks between Clerides and Denktash was
held in mid-July in Troutbeck, near New York, and the second was
held last week in Glion, near Montreux, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
In Montreux, Denktash rejected unofficial documents presented
by Cordovez on the guidelines leading to a resolution of the
Cyprus problem and threatened to walk out of the talks if he
was in any way pressured to sign them.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader also threatened that he would not
attend any further talks if accession talks between the European
Union and Cyprus go ahead as scheduled for early next year.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Cypriot government expects the Security
Council, taking into consideration the continued impasse toward a
Cyprus settlement, to examine available methods for breaking the
deadlock and implementing its resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He severely criticized both Turkey's and Denktash's attitude at
the talks, stressing that it was "completely contrary to the
spirit and the letter of the U.N.'s invitation."
</P>
<P>
Christofides reiterated the government's firm positions on the
nature of a solution of the Cyprus problem, saying that a solution
must be based on a single and indivisible sovereignty, territorial
integrity, independence, one international personality and one
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The principles are roughly the same as those pursued by the
United Nations regarding the Cyprus issue. And about 1,200
U.N. peacekeepers patrol the 180-kilometer "Green Line" between
the two Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
A settlement must also exclude union, in whole or in part, with
another country as well as partition or secession, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after the Turkish troops invaded and
took over the northern third in the wake of a short-lived
coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Appoints Special Representative to Study Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today appointed Olara Otunnu of Uganda as his Special
Representative to study the impact of armed conflict on children,
said a statement by the spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu's nomination was based on extensive consultations held
with the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human
Rights, the United Nations Children's fund (UNICEF)and the Office
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees(UNHCR), said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
At the recommendation of the General Assembly, the Special
Representative is mandated to assess progress achieved, steps
taken and difficulties encountered in strengthening the plight of
children affected by armed conflict, encourage the development of
networking, foster international cooperation to ensure respect for
children's rights in these situations and to contribute to the
coordination of efforts by Governments and relevant United Nations
bodies, specialized agencies as well as other competent bodies and
non-government organizations, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Special Representative is furthermore requested to work
closely with the Committee on the Rights of the Child and to
report annually to the General Assembly and the Commission on
Human Rights on his findings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
