<HEADLINE> Egypt Transfers 10 Million Dollars to PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has ordered a transfer of 10 million U.S. dollars at once to the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) which suffers from a
financial freeze imposed by Israel, Egypt's MENA news agency said
today.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone contact today, Mubarak informed PNA
President Yasser Arafat that he is making efforts to ease the
financial crisis through which the Palestinian government and its
people are passing through.
</P>
<P>
Israel said Monday it is to free about 30 percent of the
transfers in taxes and customs duties Israel has withheld from
Palestinian self-rule areas since the July 30 bombing in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel said the easing was in response to "partial cooperation"
in the investigation into last month's double suicide bombing, but
insisted that an end to Israel's financial blockade hinges on
whether Arafat cracks down on terrorists.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli Treasury Ministry spokesman said some 134 million
shekels (34 million dollars) has been frozen since the attack,
carried out by two suicide bombers who killed 14 other Israeli
civilians.
</P>
<P>
But Palestinian officials say Israel has kept back some 220
million shekels (62.5 million dollars) of the money, owed under a
1994 agreement on economic links between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been working with the U.S. to lift other punitive
measures, including overall closure of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. 
</P>
