<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Trade Turnover Goes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian foreign trade turnover
decreased by 3.9 percent in the first half of 1997 compared to the
same period last year, the Interfax quoted sources in the Ministry
for Foreign Economic Relations and Trade as reporting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry experts, the decrease was caused by a
number of objective economic factors, including the attainment of
maximum export quotas in most of the raw-materials branches, an
unfavorable situation for Russian exports on the world market and
the low quality of Russian products.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they said, "the Russian market has been filled with
foreign-made consumer goods, while tariff and non-tariff
regulations have been tightened to protect Russian producers.
</P>
<P>
Russian exports in January to June 1997 shrank by 2.4 percent
compared to the same period of 1996 and did not exceed 40.4
billion US dollars, according to the Russian state Statistics
Committee and customs services.
</P>
<P>
It said that Natural gas, which accounted for 21.6 percent of
Russian exports and crude oil, 18.2 percent, were the main Russian
exports.
</P>
<P>
The imports of Russia in the first half of 1997 are estimated
at 22 billion US dollars (unorganized trade not included), or 6.4
percent less than in the first half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that imports from the countries of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) have sharply decreased
and dropped by 22.4 percent compared to last year's figures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, equipment and machines were one of the few Russian
import items whose volume increased in the first half of the year,
by 0.6 percent in the same period last year to 7.1 billion US
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
