<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Pulp Industry Invests More on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Canada's pulp and paper industry
invested 685 million U.S. dollars on capital projects for
environmental protection in 1995, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
This investment represents by far the largest amount of any
Canadian industry, the federal statistics agency noted.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure was 55.3 percent higher than the amount it
spent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Its share of capital investment for environmental purposes
among Canadian industries rose from 39 percent to 42 percent in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Much of the new pulp and paper investment went into pollution
and abatement and control projects, in large part to comply with
the new environmental regulations that came into effect at the end
of 1994, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Canadian industries spent 1.6 billion dollars on
capital projects for environmental purposes in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Combined with 1.7 billion dollars in operating expenditures,
Canada's industry spending on environmental protection totaled
3.3 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In that year, Canada's crude oil and natural gas industry spent
233 million dollars on environmental protection, the second
largest of all industries.
</P>
<P>
It accounted for 14.4 percent of capital spending for
environmental purposes for the surveyed industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
