<HEADLINE> Hamburg Firm Suspected of Importing 600 Ton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A German firm in the northern port
city of Hamburg is suspected of importing 616 tons of British beef
in the past six months, violating a European Union export ban
imposed against the possible human infection of Mad Cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said the firm was suspected of having sold 116 tons
of the beef to four firms across Germany between April and June.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear yet whether any of the beef have reached the
shops. Customs officials had been instructed to seize the beef.
Last week, they seized 60 tons at the firm.
</P>
<P>
Investigators also said that documents found during a raid
showed that 440 tons of the imported beef were later shipped on
to eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Hamburg firm owner was briefly detained and released last
Thursday, who told police the beef were imported from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
But investigators believe the beef originated from Britain or
possibly northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The EU ban on British beef was imposed last year following
revelation of the possible link between Mad Cow disease and
Creutzfeldt-Jakob-Disease (CJD), the corresponding human form of
the fatal brain disorder.  
</P>
</TEXT>
