<HEADLINE> Bonn Opens Compensation Talks with Holocaust Survivors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The German government and a Jewish
group opened a two-day talks today on compensation to Holocaust
survivors now living in the former East Bloc.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's talks were held in the German Finance Ministry and
were described as preliminary prior to the Wednesday meeting
between German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of staff, Friedrich
Bohl, and representatives of the Jewish Claims Conference.
</P>
<P>
Germany has faced growing pressure to pay compensation, in the
way of pensions, to elderly Holocaust survivors in eastern Europe
and the former Soviet Union, who were excluded from the estimately
100 billion German marks (55 billion U.S. dollars) of reparations
made to western victims during the Cold War. Most of the up to
20,000 Holocaust victims live in the former East bloc.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, chairman of the Central Council of Jews in
Germany, Ignatz Bubis, called for a quick solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
"A swift solution is needed because most of the victims are
very old," Bubis said in an interview with the German Bayerische
Rundfunk radio on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
German opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens
also called on the government to swiftly approve the pensions.
</P>
<P>
While Jewish victims in the West can get a pension of 500 marks
(273 dollars) a month, those in eastern Europe were totally
excluded, said Volker Beck, a leader of the Greens.
</P>
<P>
"The Iron Curtain against eastern European victims must go down
eventually," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
