<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Corel Drops Java Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Corel Corp. has dropped
its previously announced plans to produce new versions of all its
software in the Java programming language, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the Ottawa-based company said it has developed
technology that allows software to run on any kind of operating
system or hardware from a centrally located server.
</P>
<P>
The new technology will replace its plans to write software in
Java, the universal programming language.
</P>
<P>
Code-named Remagen, the new technology allows different
versions of software programs to talk to share information, and
all the program processing and document storage will take place on
a computer server, not a desktop.
</P>
<P>
"It allows people to have low cost of ownership without giving
up functionality," Michael Cowpland, Corel's president and chief
executive, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Remagen is at the core of Corel's plan to grab a larger share
of the lucrative corporate market from its arch rival Microsoft,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The new move also suggests that Corel has abandoned its
much-publicized plan to be the first company to offer all its
software in Java.
</P>
<P>
Corel's first attempt, a Java prototype version of its Office
software, has been criticized by users as too slow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
