<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Orders to Close Embassy in Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has ordered the closedown of the country's embassy in
Conakry, capital of neighboring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, the order was
announced through a radio in Sierra Leone's capital Freetown
following the demonstrations Sierra Leonean students and others
on exile held against the junta's continued stay in power in the
embassy compound on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that the decision was made possibly because
the embassy has become a rallying point against the military
junta.
</P>
<P>
Conakry is also the place ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
chose to stay after the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, angry Sierra Leoneans who gathered in
the embassy this morning described the order to close down the
embassy as displaced, saying that the junta was irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador, a military man who was appointed by the ousted
government of Kabbah, said the embassy would remain open as
wished by Sierra Leoneans in Conakry.
</P>
<P>
The envoy's announcement was widely seen among the people in
Conakry as an attempt to discard himself from the military junta
in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
He has often been accused of collaborating with the Armed
Force Revolutionary Council, the highest governing body set up
after the coup.
</P>
<P>
The embassy compound remains as the focal point of Sierra
Leoneans in Conakry who congregate there daily to hear of news
from home and immediate fellow Sierra Leoneans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
