<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Warned Hezbollah Against Targeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today called Hezbollah's Katyusha attacks on
northern Israel this morning "a very severe violation of the
understandings" between two sides.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who toured Israeli northern border hours after the
attack, said that Israel obviously did not seek any escalation of
tensions in the area, but equally could not accept "very grave
infection" of the attacks on Israeli civilians.
</P>
<P>
"This something we can not tolerate," he stressed, adding "We
have simple principle: if there is quiet on the Israeli side of
the border, there is quiet on the Lebanese side of border."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also urged Syrian government and Lebanese government
to make all efforts to exercise control of Hezbollah, saying that
that the control would be not only in Israel's interest but also
in their two countries' interest.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah guerrillas fired Katyusha rockets into northern
Israel in two heavy waves this morning. Israeli army sources said
that at least forty rockets fell in the western Galilee and in the
Galilee panhandle.
</P>
<P>
Three Israelis were lightly hurt in the rocket attacks,
including one woman who was treated for shock, and one Lebanese
woman was more seriously injured from the shelling. But exploding
rockets caused quite some damages to buildings of the area.
</P>
<P>
It was the heaviest Katyusha attack since the cross-border
fighting in the Grape Wrath campaign some 16 months
ago. Hezbollah took responsibility for the attack, saying it was
revenging the South Lebanon Army's shelling of Sidon Monday,
killing some seven Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the April truce agreement which ended a
17-day Israeli offensive, called the Grape Wrath Campaign,
against Hezbollah, both sides are prohibited from attacking
civilian targets or launching attacks from civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, a Muslim Shiite movement backed by Iran, has been
battling to force Israel out of the buffer zone Israel set up in
south Lebanon in 1985 to prevent cross-border attacks by
anti-Israeli guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
