<HEADLINE> SADC Ministers Adopt Linear Reduction Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Ministers for industries
and trade of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
have agreed to adopt linear reduction approach in harmonizing
tariffs in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after their two-day meeting
beginning on Monday in the capital of Tanzania, according to a
statement issued at the end of the meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
The approach was found to be more predictable, simple to use
and transparent as compared to other methods, the SADC ministers
maintained.
</P>
<P>
"Linear reduction approach is more suitable compared to others
such as the harmonized internal tariff reduction methods," the
statement said, adding that the method will pave way for the
ratification of process of the protocol.
</P>
<P>
With regard to time frame, the ministers agreed that member
states of the SADC should submit lists of sensitive products to
the SADC Industry and Trade Coordinating Unit by October this
year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed on the preparation of the position
of the southern African region on the future of the relations
between Africa-Caribbean-Pacific (APC or the Lome Convention)
countries and the European Union as a contribution of an overall
APC position on the subject.
</P>
<P>
The Lome Convention approaches its full term by February of
2000, and negotiations with the APC countries are due to begin in
Autumn of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
