<HEADLINE> Israeli Aggression Against Civilians in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Syrian and Lebanon today
condemned Israeli brutal shelling of civilian targets in the
southern Lebanese city of Sidon, killing at least nine and
wounding many others.
</P>
<P>
The condemnation was made in the minutes signed by Syrian Prime
Minister Mahmoud Zobie and his Lebanese counterpart Rafiq Hariri
after their talks here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Syrian news agency said that the Syrian and
Lebanese sides have expressed their appreciation of the
steadfastness of people in south Lebanon against Israel's
aggression, offering their condolences to the families of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Both the Israeli troops and the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army
shelled Sidon, a southern Lebanese city with a population of some
200,000. The raid killed 9 civilians and injured 43 others.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also emphasized in the minutes the
importance of cooperation in the various fields, particularly the
economic domain.
</P>
<P>
The minutes revealed that the two sides had agreed on gradually
liberalizing the exchange of agricultural and industrials
goods. Accordingly, a joint committee of the Ministers of Economy,
Finance, Agriculture and Industry, as well as the directors of
customs in the two countries, will prepare a study on the
coordination and unification of custom duties levied on the
primary material used in such products.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed their satisfaction with the progress of
the work done in the projects of electrical grids. It was agreed
to provide Lebanon with some 50 megawatts for the Angar transfer
station along the recently established linkage lines.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Lebanese Coordination Authority for Economic
Cooperation began its annual session earlier in the day under the
co-chairmanship of the Syrian and Lebanese Prime Ministers.
