<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Rocket Successfully Sends Philippine Satellite into Orbit (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XICHANG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The China-made Long March 3B
rocket successfully sent a telecommunications satellite into space
from the launching center in Xichang in southwest China's Sichuan
Province at 1:50 A.M.(Beijing time) today.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication satellite was made by the US-based Space
Systems/Loral Inc. (SS/L) for the Mabuhay Philippines Satellite
Corporation (MPSC).
</P>
<P>
The success has proved that the Long March rocket, which has
the biggest carrying capacity, is capable of projecting any
satellite with a maximum weight of 5,000 kg into orbit.
</P>
<P>
It also signifies the fulfilment of the contracted task of China
Great Wall Industrial Corporation to send the telecommunications
satellite into space for the Mabuhay Communications Satellite
Corporation (Mabuhaysat).
</P>
<P>
At 1:50 A.M. this morning, the Long March 3B rocket
blasted into the sky with the Philippine communications satellite.
</P>
<P>
Initial data from the Xi'an Satellite Monitoring Center of
northwest China's Shaanxi Province 30 minutes after the
separation of the satellite from the rocket indicated that the
satellite had gone into a geo-synchronous orbit with a perigee of
205 km, an apogee of 44,771 km and a bank angle of 24.6 degrees.
</P>
<P>
The launch was the second carried out by the Long March 3B
rocket, the 46th launch by the Long March rocket family and the
12th commercial launch done by China Great Wall Industrial
Corporation for overseas clients.
</P>
<P>
The Long March 3B rocket is a new three-stage, liquid-fueled
space carrier developed by China. With the "Long March 3A" used as
the core stage, the new model also has four booster rockets used
in the first stage. The enhanced power allows for the projection
of 5,000 kg into a geo-synchronous orbit. So far, it has the
largest carrying capacity among all China-made rockets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Rocket Successfully Sends Philippine Satellite into Orbit (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts noted that today's successful launch will be of great
significance for the development of China's aerospace technology
and for expansion of the overseas commercial launch market for
China.
</P>
<P>
The maiden flight of the Long March 3B rocket on February 15,
1996 failed, due to the changes of inertial reference in the
rocket's control system. The changes caused the spacecraft to
change course, with disastrous results. Both the rocket and the
satellite were destroyed in an explosion.
</P>
<P>
The China Academy of Carrier Rocket Technology immediately
organized a group of Chinese and foreign experts to investigate
into and publicize the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
Measures have been taken by Chinese rocket makers over the past
one and a half years to improve technology and tighten the quality
control so as to ensure the liability of the rocket.
</P>
<P>
The Mabuhay satellite weights 3,770 kg. With 30 C-band
transponders and 24 Ku-band transponders, the satellite can cover
the Philippines and most areas of Asia and provide audio, video
and data transmission services after in operation.
</P>
<P>
The China Great Wall Industrial Corporation, the US's SS/L and
the MPSC of the Philippines all expressed satisfaction with the
launch of the satellite as well as their hope for further
cooperation and exchanges in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
