<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired Teachers Called to Back Turkey's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Education Minister
Hikmet Ulugbay today called on retired teachers to support the
implementation of the newly adopted eight-year compulsory
education law.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, the education minister
said that retired teachers are welcomed to return to schools
since the country is short of qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, where more than 1.3 million children start schooling
every year, needs large numbers of teachers, Ulugbay added.
</P>
<P>
The minister, whose ministry proposed the controversial
education reform bill, said that the government would encourage
people to choose the profession of teaching.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his ministry would provide financial aid to
those students from poor families to help them finish their
eight years of education.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament passed the bill Saturday with a margin of 35
votes following a heated debate, and President Suleyman Demirel
signed it into law the next day.
</P>
<P>
The new education law enraged the pro-Islamic Welfare Party
led by Necmettin Erbakan, former prime minister, and its
followers since its adoption will lead to the closure of many
schools teaching the Koran.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that the new law is part of the
government's efforts to curb the rapidly expanding fundamentalists
in the secular country.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has announced a loan of 1 billion U.S. dollars
for Turkey's eight-year education project, earlier reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
