<HEADLINE> US Fed Leaves Short-term Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) today left short-term interest rates unchanged, deciding
there was no need to dampen the current economic expansion by
raising borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. central bank's decision had been widely anticipated
given recent comments about the "exceptional" economy from Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan and the fact that the inflation is under
control.
</P>
<P>
With unemployment rate at 24-year low of 4.8 percent, inflation
so far has been a no-show in the country. Prices at the wholesale
level have fallen for an unprecedented seven straight months and
consumer prices so far this year are rising at an annual rate of
just 1.5 percent, less than half of the increase in last year.
</P>
<P>
After increasing the interest rates a tiny quarter point at its
March meeting, the U.S. Fed has been content to leave monetary
policy unchanged at its subsequent meetings in May, July and
today.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists are worrying that wage pressures may
finally start to be emerging now that unemployment has fallen to
the lowest level in nearly a quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
They said it is only a matter of time before wage and price
pressures begin to emerge.
</P>
<P>
Many economists believe the U.S. Fed will see enough threats of
inflation to start raising rates again in coming months, perhaps
as soon as their next meeting on September 30 or by the November
12 session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
