<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Leaves Repo Rate Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank today
decided to leave its key money market interest rate, the
securities repurchase rate, unchanged at three percent, a move
which will bring some relief to money traders who are fearing of
an imminent tightening of German monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after weeks of speculations that the
German central bank, the Bundesbank, was preparing to raise
interest rates in order to arrest strong rises in consumer prices
and check the German mark's steady decline against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
But the inflation danger appear to be easing up as Bundesbank
said on Tuesday that Germany's M3 money supply, which serves as a
key indicator for future inflationary trends, was under control
after growing at an annual rate of 5.7 percent in July, down from
6.4 percent in June and 7.0 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
With the repurchase rate fixed, financial markets are now
refocusing attention on Thursday meeting of the Bundesbank's
central council, which would make decision on the country's two
other benchmark rates, the discount rate and the Lombard rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
