<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's MPs Threaten to Veto New Cabinet Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran's liberal-minded President
Mohammad Khatami today confronted stern challenge from the
Parliament dominated by conservatives who threatened to veto
one-fifth of his proposed 22 cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
This is the first battle for Khatami to fight with rightist
hardliners for his new government since he was sworn in office on
August 4.
</P>
<P>
This would also be the first time for an Iranian president to
face such tremendous pressure from the opposition camp headed by
his presidential election rival Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar
Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
The major controversial point between the 54-year-old president
and the rightist camp in the heated parliamentary debate today was
his proposed candidate for the Ministry of Culture and Islamic
Guidance liberal author and journalist Ata'ollah Mohajerani.
</P>
<P>
But behind the open debate is the fierce power struggle
between the two camps because the rightist camp suffered a
miserable defeat in the presidential election on May 23. It does
not want to lose any field in the political arena, especially the
key posts such as foreign minister, interior minister, defense
minister, information minister and cultural minister.
</P>
<P>
Rightist parliament members (MP) today pounded Mohajerani for
his past liberal record and digged up dirt by reminding the nation
of his past association with the outlawed Mojahedin Khalq
Organization (MKO), an opposition group which has waged war
against Islamic government for the past 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani also came under attack for having supported the idea
of direct talks with the U.S. and promoting liberal ideas in his
defunct weekly called Bahman, which was published for about 10
weeks in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Another member of Khatami's cabinet that came under fire
today was his proposed interior minister Abdollah Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Nouri is the leader of a minority leftist-liberal faction in
the Iranian Parliament called Majma'e Hezbollah (Association of
the Party of God). He served as Interior Minister between 1989
and 1993.
</P>
<P>
The rightists attacked Nouri for a number of things including
his nonchalant attitude toward the MP's and his having gained
his son's military exemption through influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
Eesa Kalantari, Khatami proposed minister of agriculture, was
also under attack for lack of planning on agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The rightist MP's today also took turns at attacking the
credential of Khatami's proposed housing and urban development
minister Ali Abdolalizadeh who is now serving as Governor General
of the northwestern Iranian province of Eastern Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Abdolalizadeh failed to gain the approval of the influential
Guardian Council to run in Parliament elections of 1991.
</P>
<P>
The rejection by the 12-member Guardians Council is viewed by
the rightists as a sign that Abdolalizadeh is not considered
worthy for ministerial posts.
</P>
<P>
Although the rightists freely criticized all of the four
ministers above, they were a bit more cautious about attacking
Hossein Mozaffar, Khatami's proposed minister for education.
</P>
<P>
He was praised by both camps as a veteran of the war and as a
man who lost his three brothers in Iran-Iraq war (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Khatami would have a hard time
gaining the Parliament's approval for important ministries such
as interior and cultural ministers because the rightist camp
headed by Nateq-Nouri controls about 150 seats of the 270-seat
Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
