<HEADLINE> Three US Libraries Receive Extraordinary Chinese Gifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Three major American libraries
have received extraordinary gifts of the Treasure of Chinese
Classics, one of the most significant publications in Chinese
history, library officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The gifts were presented to representatives of the New York
Public Library, the Boston Public Library and Harvard University's
Yenching Library by the Chinese Association for Promoting of
Culture Exchange and Cooperation, the United World Chinese
Association and China's Cheng Cheng Enterprises Holdings at a
ceremony at the Marriot World Trade Center Monday night.
</P>
<P>
A limited edition of 10,000 copies, the Treasure of Chinese
Classics is truly the most significant and consummate magnum opus
in Chinese publishing history. It represents the concerted efforts
of more than 3,700 scholars and experts in Chinese cultural
circles.
</P>
<P>
Organized by subject, the set of 123 illustrated volumes
contains 276 million words in Chinese, representing the best
editions of more than 1,000 classical titles covering history,
philosophy, Buddhism, Taoism, arts, literature, medicine, war,
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
It covers a 5,000 years span of the quintessence of Chinese
culture dating from ancient China to modern times.
</P>
<P>
The gifts add a major strength to the three U.S. libraries'
Chinese language collections and will benefit numbers of users
from many parts of the United States and the world, library
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
