nine civilians and wounded 43 others, and an Israeli complaint
about Lebanon's retaliation against the southern town of Jezzine
which is occupied by Israeli-backed South Lebanese Army (SLA).
</P>
<P>
The five-nation committee, comprising of delegates from the
U.S., France, Syria, Israel and Lebanon, was set up under a
ceasefire accord brokered by the U.S. to end a 16-day Israeli
blitz against Lebanon in April last year.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister warned that if the already
worsened situation continues, Lebanon will consider submitting a
complaint against Israel to the U.N. Security council and its
assembly.
</P>
<P>
Israel strongly denied firing the shells and blamed it on the
SLA, saying the SLA's fire was without the knowledge of the
Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
But the Lebanese Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
insisted that the SLA made the attack after obtaining the
permission of Israel.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Saida held mourning and funeral
ceremonies today for the victims of the shelling, including a
six-year-old boy, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Faisl Soia, governor of the South Province, attended the funeral
as the representative of Lebanese President Elias Hrawi and the
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
