<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Still Meets EMU Criteria: OECD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Germany is set to go beyond debt
and deficit limits required for joining the single European
currency, but could still be a founding member of the 1999
European Monetary Union (EMU)
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
(OECD) in a report today expected Germany's budget deficit this
year to be 3.25 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) and
overall public debt to rise to 62 percent of GDP, exceeding the
deficit limit of 3 percent of GDP and the debt limit of 60 percent
under the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, "The difference from 3 percent is
well within the range of normal statistical revision so at this
deficit level the criterion could be effectively regarded as being
met."
</P>
<P>
"We would regard 3.2 percent as meeting the criteria," Robert
Price and Grant Kirkpatrick, the authors of the report, told
reporters in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
It has long been accepted that Germany would not make the 60
percent public debt limit, because of the dear costs of
unification.
</P>
<P>
Bonn has insisted that it would cut back public spending to
meet the budget deficit limit, but the OECD report deemed this
impossible, citing lower than expected tax revenue and the high
costs of paying unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
Based on full fiscal and economic data from 1997, it will be
decided in May 1998 which European Union countries will join the
single European currency, the euro, which is due to be launched in
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The OECD also noted, "The acceptability of the 1997 budget
outcome should be judged on the basis of whether the underlying
fiscal position is sustainable in 1998 and beyond -- not just in
terms of debt and deficit... but also in terms of tax and
expenditure goals."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the OECD report expected Germany's GDP to grow by
2.25 percent this year and 2.75 percent in 1998, thanks to
continued strong exports. Domestic demand will remain low as a
result of Germany's record joblessness.
</P>
<P>
Germany's unemployment would remain at the current level of 4.3
million, and drop to 4.2 million, or 10.9 percent, in 1998,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
