<HEADLINE> Britain: Montserrat Evacuation to Begin Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The British government announced
here today that a voluntary evacuation from the volcano-stricken
Caribbean island of Montserrat will begin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview this afternoon, Britain's
International Development Secretary Clare Short said, "A voluntary
evacuation system will start tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
"People will be helped to go to Antigua, be received there,
looked after, fed and housed and then given choices about their
longer term decisions," she said.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that those Montserrat residents would be given
the choice of settling elsewhere in neighboring Caribbean
countries or in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The volcano, which was dormant for 400 years until 1995, has
killed at least 19 people and virtually destroyed the whole
country. A decision to launch a large-scale evacuation was made
last week when new scientific advice suggested that a massive
eruption was approaching.
</P>
<P>
The island's population is sharply down to less than half the
11,000 residents living there before the volcano became active in
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
