<HEADLINE> World Population Totals 5.75 Billion in Mid-1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The world population was
estimated at 5.751 billion in mid-1996, 0.61 percent more than the
mid-year estimates in 1995, the UN Statistics Division reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that the 10 most-populous countries
each with over 100 million people have a combined population of
3.44 billion while people of the 13 countries, each with a
population between 50 and 100 million, number 834 million. The
population of the 23 countries in the two groups above amounts to
4.249 billion, nearly three quarters of the world total.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 biggest countries, India with a population of
944.58 million came first in terms of absolute growth, registering
an increase 15.58 million people. In terms of growth rate,
Pakistan took first place with an increase of 2.99 percent over
the figure in the previous year, while Nigeria recorded 2.95
percent growth, ranking second.
</P>
<P>
China's population numbered 1.232 billion in mid-1996, 10.58
million more than in the previous year. Its growth rate of 0.86
percent was lowest among main developing countries and only higher
than Japan and the Russian Federation among the 10 leading
countries.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the third most populous country, recorded a
1.28 percent growth or an increase of 3.39 million. Its population
came to 266.56 million in the latest mid-year estimates.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 most populous countries, the Russian Federation
was the only country registering negative growth of population.
The mid-year estimates show that the population of the Russian
Federation was 147.74 million, compared to 148.14 million a year
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
