<HEADLINE> Curfew Imposed in S. Leonean Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's capital
Freetown and its surrounding towns and villages in the western
areas have been put under a 10:00 p. m. to 6:00 a. m. curfew with
immediate effect by the military government, a radio report said
today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement made on State Radio today said that the
curfew "is as a result of the current security situation."
</P>
<P>
The release also warned soldiers "harassing peaceful citizens
will be made to face the full penalty of the law."
</P>
<P>
It also said any "soldier or civilian caught looting will be
shot on the spot" while any soldier or armed civilian caught
commandeering or making any attempt to commandeer any civilian
vehicle will be shot on sight without warning or explanation."
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Defense Department "is
determined to enforce harsh measures to contain any situation
designed to give the (military) government a bad image."
</P>
<P>
The military junta did not give any explanation for the
announced measures, but observers said the regime has come under
increasing threat by Nigerian soldiers based in two points near
the capital and it feared an imminent attack following the
sweeping visits to Cote d'Iviore and Guinea on Monday by Nigerian
leader Sani Abacha. 
</P>
