<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marco Polo: Tibet is Province of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian medieval traveler Marco
Polo wrote in his travel notes more than 700 years ago that Tibet
was a "province" of China, a Chinese researcher has claimed.
</P>
<P>
Wang Gui, a research fellow at the Military Academy of
Sciences, made the discovery in the English version of "Il
milione," or "Travels of Marco Polo," and shared his find today at
the ongoing 1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies.
</P>
<P>
The term "Province of Tibet" can be seen on page 172 of
"Travels of Marco Polo," published by the MacMillan Company in
1927, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Marco Polo wrote his world famous "Travels of Marco Polo" in
1298. It is the earliest European account of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The book's 1948 edition, published by John Company of New York,
also mentions the "Province of Tibet".
</P>
<P>
In his book, Polo wrote, "The Province of Tibet is also under
the jurisdiction of the Great Khan."
</P>
<P>
Wang said the find is "extremely valuable, because the Travels
of Marco Polo is a believable history book."
</P>
<P>
"Kubla Khan trusted Polo very much, therefore Polo was familiar
with the local folk customs and traditions. He also traveled to
some areas inhabited by Tibetan people," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Marco Polo went overland to China across the Pamirs and the
Gobi Desert. After 17 years of itinerant service for Kubla Khan,
he returned home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Stresses Stabilizing North Caucasus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today stressed the necessity of stabilizing the North Caucasus,
saying that its settlement is essential to Russia's national
security.
</P>
<P>
Dissatisfied with the situation, Yeltsin said at a meeting of
the Security Council that conditions there were slowly returning
to normal, but it remained an explosive region.
</P>
<P>
There are "quite a few hotbeds of tension" in the North
Caucasus -- above all, Chechnya, the zone of the Ossetian-Ingush
conflict and Dagestan, where the situation is extremely
complicated, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Security Council must work out a common Caucasian
approach to solve regional problems.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also said the Interior Ministry, the Federal Security
Service, the Federal Border Service and the State Customs
Committee did not properly coordinate their actions in their
efforts to restore stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
For lack of a single coordinating center between these
agencies, the president complained that he often received
diversified and sometimes contradictory information on the
situation in the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
All this "is extremely alarming, as Russia's integrity is at
stake," Yeltsin warned.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation in this region must be resolved in a way
that would not breach the interests of Russia's national security.
</P>
<P>
"All agencies without exception must take serious, additional
measures and efforts to stabilize the situation." the president
added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the interests of many countries, "Not only
those of our Commonwealth, but of foreign countries as well," were
interwoven in this region.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is claiming that the North Caucasus is a zone in its
interests. As our interest fades, the U.S., on the contrary, is
making moves to penetrate this zone and is openly speaking about
this," Yeltsin noted.
</P>
<P>
On the Chechen issue, Yeltsin said it was extremely important
to conclude a large-scale treaty between Chechnya and the federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission drafting the treaty will be comprised of
Security Council Secretary Ivan Rybkin, Head of the Presidential
Administration Valentin Yumashev, Minister for Nationalities
Vyacheslav Mikhailov and Deputy Prime Minister Ramazan Abdulatipov.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the commission must do its work "insistently,
confidently and scrupulously." 
</P>
</TEXT>
