<HEADLINE> German Economy Increasingly Dependent on Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economy has become
increasingly dependent on foreign markets with exports expected to
account for over 28 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) this
year, an umbrella organization of German trade unions said today.
</P>
<P>
German exports expanded by 20 percent from 1993 to 1996 and are
expected to grow seven to 10 percent this year, Michael Geuenich,
a member of the organization said.
</P>
<P>
The boom in exporting is the best evidence of Germany's
competitiveness on the world market, Geuenich said.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted that the economy's dependence on world markets
carried the risk that an economic setback in foreign countries
could also take its toll in Germany.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore necessary to achieve a balanced relationship
between exports and imports in order to ensure a sustained
economic upswing, Geuenich said, adding that the government should
take measures to spur private spending and increase state
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
