<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Fails to Agree on Compensation to Holocaust Survivors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The German government has failed to
reach a comprehensive agreement with a Jewish group on
compensating Holocaust survivors now living in Eastern Europe, but
agreed to continue negotiations, a German official said today.
</P>
<P>
"There is still no agreement," said Friedrich Bohl, German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of staff, after two days of talks
with the Jewish Claims Conference.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to set up a joint commission to make
recommendations on a detailed solution to the issue within three
months, he added.
</P>
<P>
Germany is currently under growing pressure from the United
States and Jewish groups to compensate elderly Holocaust survivors
in east European countries and the former Soviet Union, who were
excluded from compensation made to Western victims during the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
According to government figures, Germany has paid about 100
billion German marks (55 billion U.S. dollars) to Holocaust
survivors in the West since 1949.
</P>
<P>
After Germany was reunited, Bonn offered a one-time payment to
Holocaust survivors in Russia and parts of Eastern Europe, but
Jewish groups and the U.S. government say that has not been enough.
</P>
<P>
Jewish groups want Holocaust survivors in the former East Bloc
to be eligible for monthly German pensions of 500 marks (270
dollars), the same as Nazi victims in the West. The estimated
numbers of Holocaust survivors in Eastern Europe range from 15,000
to 40,000.
</P>
<P>
Bohl, however, ruled out the possibility of paying monthly
pension to Nazi victims in Eastern Europe. Instead, he suggested
that Bonn would agree to offer one-time payments to them.
</P>
<P>
Israel Singer, chief negotiator of the Jewish group, said after
the talks that "What we've achieved today is a framework for the
solution of a moral problem.... We must work hard in the next 90
days to show the world that we are tackling moral problems in a
moral way."
</P>
<P>
The German opposition Greens Party, however, sharply criticized
the Bonn government for delaying a solution for another three
months. Such a delay was unacceptable because many of the elderly
victims die every day, the Greens said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
