<HEADLINE> China Should Expand Mineral Resources Development: Minister (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China will in the next decade
invest several billion yuan in geological prospecting in the
western areas and the development of mineral resources badly
needed by its economy, said the country's top mining official.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, efforts should also be made to attract more
overseas investors to finance development of the country's mineral
resources, Song Ruixiang, minister of geology and mineral
resources, said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said the state has been drafting rules and regulations on
encouraging overseas investors to put money in China's geological
projects.
</P>
<P>
"China will also intensify its plan to go abroad for
prospecting and developing mineral resources and strive to
alleviate the pressure from the ever-growing demand for minerals
by the way of comprehensive, multi-channel cooperation," Song said.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, China has suffered a deficit of 10
billion U.S. dollars in trade for mineral commodities, and related
energy and raw materials, according to statistics, which also show
that China has become the world's second-largest consumer of
mineral products.
</P>
<P>
Song said he believes that at the dawn of the 21st century,
China will face a "serious situation" in terms of availability of
mineral products and resources. But conducting geological
exploration and development projects on overseas land will be "one
of the major strategic measures taken to guarantee a safe,
long-term and stable supply of mineral resources in China."
</P>
</TEXT>
