<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: American Couple Make 61st Trip to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordan Phillips and his wife
Mary will leave here in a few days on their 61st trip to China.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, the American couple has visited the country
regularly, two or three times a year. They have been to all 31
provinces and autonomous regions in the country, including Tibet,
where they toured four times.
</P>
<P>
The numbers may sound astonishing, but for Phillips and his
wife, who are keen to learn about China, the best way to
understand a country is to go there and see it for oneself.
</P>
<P>
"Hearsay is not reliable," Phillips, an emeritus professor of
obstetrics and gynecology at the University of California, and the
chairman and founder of the American Association of Gynecologic
Laparoscopists, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The trips have made them experts on China, particularly on
Chinese medicine and the country's modern health and medical
conditions.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 years, they have given hundreds of lectures
about Chinese medicine in hospitals and research institutes in and
out of the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We know that China is experiencing a transition from an
undeveloped country to one that is on the road of rapid
development," Phillips said, adding: "What has impressed us most,
however, is the fact that China is interested in improving the
quality of life for its people."
</P>
<P>
Phillips stressed that medical and health care conditions in
China have improved over the past decade, citing the fact that
brand new 100- to 1,000-bed hospitals are being built. Chinese
doctors are open-minded and able to keep up with the latest
developments in the field of medicine, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on her impressions of China, Mary Phillips said the
Chinese people opened their hearts to them and accepted them as
real friends. She talked about the history of their ties with
China, which stemmed from an accident in 1979 when they first
visited the country.
</P>
<P>
During that visit, they found that medical texts and reference
books in medical schools were far from sufficient. Deeply
interested in medical education, the couple made up their minds to
provide more books for China.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, they set up a nonprofit corporation, Medical Books for
China, which called on U.S. libraries to donate books to China.
The company has been growing ever since. So far it has sent a
total of 960 tons of medical, dental, nursing, veterinarian,
pharmacy, basic science books, journals, videotapes, and other
educational materials.
</P>
<P>
Phillips said he and his wife have made some 1,500 Chinese
friends over the years. He also believes that the ties between
the United States and China will grow.
</P>
<P>
"The problem I see is that some people talk about China but
they have never been there," he said,"How do you know what you are
talking about if you have never been to the place?"
</P>
<P>
Mary, a photographer and poet, is more concerned about China's
future. She said that China is moving toward commercialization,
but fortunately a thread of traditional culture still exists.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this thread of Chinese culture will never be lost, and
the strong family ties will still remain," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
