<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBF to Apply New Scoring System in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 20 (xinhua) -- The International Badminton
Federation (IBF) will apply the new scoring system for singles
events in the 1997 World Cup badminton championships which opened
in Yogyakarta of Indonesia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
IBF official Jeff Robson told a press conference that the new
scoring system, which was tried out in the 1996 World Cup in
Jakarta, benefits the television station which broadcasts the
games live with airing commercials during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
The new scoring system allows a 90-second timeout in each set
when eight points have been collected in the men's singles, while
it was 60-second for a women's singles set after six points have
been reached.
</P>
<P>
"If players, coaches and the community give a good response to
the application of this scoring system, it will continue. If all
are against it, it will be stopped," Robson said.
</P>
<P>
Under the old system, a deuce in the men's singles will occur
in the position of 13-13 or 14-14, but under the current one, the
deuce will occur only in 14-14, in which the first player to
collect 14 points may opt for a deuce of one point or three points.
</P>
<P>
In the women's singles, the deuce in the old system will occur
in 9-9 or 10-10, but in the new system the deuce will occur only
in been reached in each set.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 countries and regions will take part in the
200,000 U.S. dollars World Cup event, which ends at August 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Tibetan Diagnosis Deciphered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Blood testing is almost always
required nowadays to accurately diagnose poisoning, but in ancient
Tibet, the only thing needed to make the call was saliva.
</P>
<P>
According to newly-deciphered ancient Tibetan medical classics,
people living on the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau some 1,000 years ago
could determine if poisoning had occurred by spitting into a
bronze bowl full of water.
</P>
<P>
If the saliva remained on the surface of the water after a
certain period of time, no problem, no poison. If the saliva sank
to the bottom of the bowl, the person was poisoned, but not too
seriously. If the saliva was suspended in the middle of the water,
things looked grim.
</P>
<P>
And to determine the exact cause of poisoning, a victim simply
had to spit onto a finely-textured white stone which had been
heated. If the saliva in the cracks of the stone turned black
after it cooled, the person had been poisoned.
</P>
<P>
"The method is simple, but feasible," says Luo Bingfen, an
associate professor with the Central University for Nationalities
who deciphered the ancient medical classics.
</P>
<P>
The classics were found in a cave in the Mogao Grottos in
Dunhuang, northwest China's Gansu Province, in the early 1900s and
were later looted by Britain and then India.
</P>
<P>
Luo's translation, based on copies of the original text,
includes more than 40 diagnoses and cures for ailments such as
heart, liver, and lung diseases, bone fractures, constant
nosebleeds, skin problems and impotence.
</P>
<P>
Other treatments can also be found in the translation for
people suffering from attempted hanging, those who have nearly
drowned, or people who have been bitten by a mad dog.
</P>
<P>
Luo has also delivered a thesis to the 1997 Beijing Seminar on
Tibetan Studies, which opened here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
