<HEADLINE> Arabs Hail Egypt's Aid to PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Arab leaders today hailed Egypt's
transfer of 10 million U.S. dollars to the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) which is subject to Israel's economic sanctions,
calling on other countries to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted Arab League Secretary
General Abdel Meguid as expressing the hope that all Arab
leaderships would cooperate to provide the PNA with financial aid
to "enable it stand up to the (Israeli) collective punishment."
</P>
<P>
Meguid said he held intensive contacts with Arab foreign
ministers Tuesday on efforts to offer immediate financial
assistance to the PNA, in response to PNA President Yasser
Arafat's report two days ago on the deteriorating economic
conditions in the self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
In Gaza today, Arafat praised the Egypt's decision on Tuesday
of the fund transfer to ease the suffering of the besieged
Palestinians and voiced confidence that the Arab nation will
support the Palestinian people at this tough phase.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zuhdie Al Qudra said President
Hosni Mubarak's initiative sets an incentive for other Arab
leaders and monarchs to offer more aid for their Palestinian
brothers.
</P>
<P>
"The move implies a strategic and political significance for
all those seeking a fair and prevailing peace in the Mideast,
including the United States," Kamal said.
</P>
<P>
Adel Attia, chairman of the Palestinian Trade Union here, said
the Egyptian contribution will have great impact in alleviating
the Palestinian economic crises as a result of the collective
punishment policies carried out by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will host on September 7 the emergency meeting of the
Central Council of the International Confederation of Arab Trade
Unions to forge out an Arab stand towards the Israeli measures,
according to Attia.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli Treasury Ministry spokesman has said some 134
million shekels (34 million dollars) in taxes and custom duties
due to the PNA has been frozen since the July 30 attack in a
Jerusalem market carried out by two suicide bombers who killed 14
other Israeli civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
