<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Drug Committee Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Embattled Philippine Senator
Vicente Sotto today resigned as chairman of the Senate Committee
on Illegal Drugs among the accusations on his alleged linkage with
drug syndicates.
</P>
<P>
Sotto announced in a speech before the Senate that he will
inhibit himself from the proceedings of the Senate Select
Committee which is presently investigating allegations linking
some senators to the illegal drug trade.
</P>
<P>
But he asked the Select Committee to allow his legal counsel to
audit the proceedings and represent him during the Senate
hearings.
</P>
<P>
He also challenged the law enforcement agents investigating his
case to charge him in court rather than utilizing the evidence
against him.
</P>
<P>
Sotto was the first senator to be implicated as the protector
of the country's suspected drug godfather Alfredo Tiongco in the
intensive movement launched against illegal drugs during the past
months.
</P>
<P>
He was dragged into the illegal drug controversy after his
chief security officer, Fernando Vinculado, was discovered to be
working allegedly as Tiongco's protector.
</P>
<P>
Vinculado was the head of the Liaison Office created to
coordinate between the Senate Committee on Illegal Drugs and the
Narcotics Command of the Philippine National Police regarding
operations taken against illegal drug syndicates.
</P>
<P>
But Sotto has strongly denied having any direct link with
Vinculado and Tiongco.
</P>
<P>
Senator Juan Ponce Enrile, who is presently the chairman of the
Senate Ways and Means Committee, will replace Sotto as the
chairman of the Illegal Drugs Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
