<HEADLINE> SAS Increases Cargo Service to/from Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MACAO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Scandinavian Airlines System
(SAS) announced today that it has increased its cargo service to
and from Macao to three times a week from two.
</P>
<P>
The SAS said in a press release that the increase of cargo
flights from and to the Macao International Airport was in
response to the heavy demand from the regional market.
</P>
<P>
The new cargo flight will be routed between Gothenburg in
Sweden and Macao, via Sharjah. Its previous two flights, which was
commenced on June 3, 1996, stop over in Macao but continue on to
Osaka.
</P>
<P>
The release said SAS was the first airline to operate
scheduled cargo flights from Macao airport. The freighter
operation from Macao complements the five passenger flights a week
non-stop from Hong Kong to Copenhagen with Boeing 767-300s, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The cargo plane, Boeing 747-200SF, has a cargo capacity of 100
tons. It arrives in Macao on Mondays, Thursdays and Saturdays, and
departs on Wednesdays, Fridays and Sundays, respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
