<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Malaysia's Current Account Deficit Likely to Exceed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's current account
deficit for 1997 may exceed the forecast by the government if the
local currency ringgit continues to weaken, Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad said today.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government forecast this year's current account
deficit to be 14.8 billion ringgit (about 5.48 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The deficit may be bigger because the ringgit is being kept
pushing down and the cost of imports is much higher, Mahathir told
reporters after launching a pictorial book on Former Malaysian
Prime Minister Tun Abdul Razak here.
</P>
<P>
Several Malaysian economists predicted that the deficit might
even reach between 25 billion ringgit (about 9.26 billion U.S.
dollars) and 27 billion ringgit (about 10 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Statistics Department of Malaysia reported today that the
current account recorded a deficit of 1.8 billion ringgit (about
670 million U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of this year, a
marked improvement over the 4.5 billion ringgit (about 1.67
billion U.S. dollars) in the fourth quarter of last year and 3.2
billion ringgit (about 1.185 billion U.S. dollars) for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said "but we have to look at what it is going to be
like by the end of this year."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir criticized once again speculators like American
financier George Soros for speculative attacks on currencies in
the region.
</P>
<P>
He said these speculators had huge amounts of money in their
hands to undermine the economies of many developing countries,
including Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Now even South Korea is the latest to suffer, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They are crooks who are out to make money for themselves at
the expense of the poor people. And of course, developed countries
are cheering him (Soros) on," Mahathir said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
