<HEADLINE> Canadian Firms Seek Partners in Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The newly-formed Canadian
Alliance for Business in Southern Africa (CABSA) said here today
there is growing interest among Canadian businesses to link up
with local companies.
</P>
<P>
Project coordinator for CABSA Emily Evans told the Zimbabwean
News Agency business contacts have been made between the two
countries in mining, construction, information technology,
cleaning services, printing and publishing sectors.
</P>
<P>
She said, ''Canadian companies are interested in looking for
business partners in southern Africa, and just recently we
notified relevant Zimbabwean companies from different sectors and
we expected them to respond any time from now.''
</P>
<P>
Evans said at the moment there has not been much on
franchising developments, but said they are currently waiting for
information from Canada on a company that intends to set up an
airline and another one in the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
Business developments are in the range of five million U.S.
Dollars each.
</P>
<P>
With more than 3,000 members throughout Canada, CABSA's main
objective is the creation of long term strategic business
alliances between Canadian and southern African firms.
</P>
<P>
Evans said besides franchising, CABSA could also consider
business cooperation proposals covering joint-ventures,
licensing, technology transfer, direct investment and training.
</P>
