<HEADLINE> Flood Death Toll Rises to 14 in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Death toll from massive floods
has risen to 14 in the northern Philippines while thousands of
residents continued to fight rising flood waters, local media
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The reported death toll was five more than the latest figure
released by the National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC). The
council put the casualties at nine dead and five injuries.
</P>
<P>
But the local Sky Cable television reported in its evening news
cast that a total of 14 lives have been claimed by the widespread
flooding which was triggered incessant monsoon rains during the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the fatalities were mostly drowned victims and
from Metro Manila or the national capital area and its nearby
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported a new landslide caused by
flash floods today in Subic, about 100 kilometers north of Manila,
which killed a young girl and a seven-year-old boy and injured
several others.
</P>
<P>
The agency earlier reported a landslide in Batangas city, Metro
Manila, on Tuesday, burying alive an old woman and injuring her
husband.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos today approved the release of 10 million
pesos (about 330,000 U.S. dollars) for the relief services and the
rehabilitation of various infrastructure damaged by the big flood.
</P>
<P>
The widespread flooding has submerged many low-lying towns and
villages, forcing more than 21,000 families or 111,000 residents
to be evacuated to safer places, according to the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said thousands of troops and social workers have been
rushed to flood-stricken areas to help rescue and relief
operation. The council estimated preliminary economic losses at
nearly 6 million pesos (about 200,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Life in most parts of Metro Manila has returned to normal as
flood waters began to subside with rains easing. But some
low-lying villages in the capital area were still under
roof-top-deep water, television footage showed.
</P>
<P>
Two dike breaches were reported as two rivers swollen by mud
flows overflowed, one in Pampanga Province and the other in Lubao
Province, inundating at least 14 villages and towns today.
</P>
<P>
Weathermen said usually moderate monsoon rains have been
intensified by super typhoon Winnie which spared the country and
is now slamming Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
They cautioned the country against more rains during the next
few days as a new typhoon Luming is gathering strength in South
China Sea northwest of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
This is the second big flood stricken the country since January
this year. In late May, torrential rains spawned by typhoon Bining
also brought about a massive flooding in the northern Philippines,
killing 24 people and injuring dozens of others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
