<HEADLINE> Crocodile Industry Seeks to Expand in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's small crocodile
farming community, buoyed by its growing stature, is now seeking
to expand and increase its membership to include black
small-scale farmers, an official said today.
</P>
<P>
Crocodile Farmers Association of Zimbabwe (CFAZ) Executive
Manager Chris Foot said his organization is going out to lure
black Zimbabweans into breeding the reptiles whose export
earnings hit the six million U.S. Dollars mark last year.
</P>
<P>
Foot said the CFAZ had produced a model guide to crocodile
farming obtainable free of charge to Zimbabweans to encourage
blacks to venture into crocodile farming.
</P>
<P>
Exports during 1996 included 38,416 skins and 38,561 kg of
meat, Foot said, adding importers were Japan, Singapore, Europe
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
''This year we hope to see a two to five percent increase
above the production for 1996,'' foot said.
</P>
<P>
Crocodiles are reared in the Zambezi valley, south-eastern
low veld and in the central regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
