<HEADLINE> Sudanese Rebels Reject Talks With Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The head of Sudan's exiled
opposition said today two major opposition parties have rejected
offers for dialog with the Sudanese government as a way to end 14
years of civil war in Africa's largest country.
</P>
<P>
"The Ummah and Unionist parties rejected mediation by some Arab
states for bilateral dialog with Khartoum," Mohamed Othman
el-Mirghani, leader of the Sudanese National Democratic Alliance
(NDA) told reporters before leaving here after a visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to Sudanese President Omar Hassan al-Bashir's
call for a ceasefire in the war with Sudan People's Liberation
Army (SPLA) rebels, led by John Garang in the south of the
country, during a visit to South Africa on August 12.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali Osman Mohammad Taha said Sunday
peace talks between the government and SPLA had been
postponed. The talks had been scheduled for August 19 in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Mirghani is president of the Cairo-based NDA, an umbrella group
of northern and southern opposition parties including Ummah Party,
SPLA, the Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) and other groups.
</P>
<P>
Mirghani said he had met with President Hosni Mubarak and
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa to discuss the situation in Egypt's
neighbor Sudan during the week-long visit.
</P>
<P>
He also met ambassadors of member states of the
Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD), a group of
African countries working on an initiative to end the war, being
fought mostly in the south and northeast.
</P>
<P>
Mirghani said he conveyed the NDA view in letters to the
presidents of Uganda, Kenya, Eritrea and the prime minister of
Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
