<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Trying to Ensure Education for Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The government is trying to
ensure children's access to education, health care and good
nutrition, and tackle the issue of child labor, Nepali Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a function to mark the queen's mother's 70th
birthday and the 33rd National Children's Day, Chand also urged
the guardians to give their due attention to the children's basic
rights.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has been paying special attention to the
problems facing children.
</P>
<P>
Included in the Ninth Five Year Plan (1997-2002) are such
programs as drafting a law on child labor, ending the tendency to
use child workers, helping children in dire straits and generally
improving their living standards, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government is also ready to launch a program to counter the
exploitation of children and help solving the problem of street
children, he added.
</P>
<P>
Of the total eight million children in Nepal, 5.5 million do
not go to school and five million have to work to support their
families, a survey shows.
</P>
<P>
And more than 7,000 children are in a sad plight as street
children, figures show.
</P>
<P>
Now the Children's Rights Coordination Committees have been set
up in 66 of the 75 districts of the country.
</P>
<P>
And five Children's Homes under Nepal Children's Organization
are accommodating 400 children, it is learnt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
