<HEADLINE> Profile: Kharrazi, Iran's New Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Kamal Kharrazi, who served as
Iran's permanent representative and ambassador to the United
Nations, today became the country's fourth foreign minister since
the founding of the Islamic Republic in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old minister secured 241 votes out of 266 votes
in the 270-member Parliament which is dominated by conservatives
headed by Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi and his team from Iran's Mission to the United
Nations played an important role in bringing about the landslide
victory of Iran's new President Mohammad Khatami on May 23
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
As opposed to Kharrazi, his predecessor Ali Akbar Velayati
sided with Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri, Khatami's rival in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Born in the Iranian capital city of Tehran in 1944, Kamal
Kharrazi served in different capacities during 1978-80, including
deputy for Planning of Islamic Republic of Iran Broadcasting
(IRIB), political deputy at the Foreign Ministry and managing
director of the Center for the Intellectual Development of
Children and Young Adults.
</P>
<P>
During the eight-year Iran-Iraq war (1980-88), Kharrazi was
appointed as a member of the Supreme Defense Council as well as
head of the War Propaganda Headquarters in the Supreme Defense
Council.
</P>
<P>
From 1980 to 1989, Kharrazi served as the managing director of
the state-run news agency -- Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA).
</P>
<P>
Since September 1989 to August 1997, he served as Iran's
Permanent Representative and Ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
While serving in this post, he held such responsibilities as
Deputy of the General Assembly, Deputy for the World Summit on
Ecology and Development, President of the Conference on
Aggression and Defense, members of Bosnia Contact Group and
member of the Board of Trustee of the U.N. School.
</P>
<P>
He is married with two sons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
