<HEADLINE> NATO Forces Help Inspect Serb Police Facilities in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- NATO-led SFOR troops
participated earlier today in simultaneous inspections on all the
Serb police facilities in Banja Luka, according to a NATO press
release available here.
</P>
<P>
The inspected facilities included three police stations, a
police academy as well as the local police and public security
headquarters in the Bosnian Serb town.
</P>
<P>
The inspections were conducted when the United Nations
International Police Task Force (UNIPTF) reported evidence of
serious criminal activities on the part of local police including
illegal interception of Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic's
telephone calls, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO forces were on hand to provide security by surrounding
the police facilities as early reports said.
</P>
<P>
The inspection will not last longer than it is necessary, the
press release said, while SFOR troops continue to operate routine
patrols and maintain a "secure environment."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Bosnian Serb president invited officials from
the U.N. peace mission and the high representative office of the
international community and briefed them about her concerns
regarding the irregularities of local police.
</P>
<P>
The local police stations have reportedly been used by
supporters of Bosnian Serb wartime leader Radovan Karadzic.
Karadzic's loyals are against Plavsic. 
