<HEADLINE> Becker Withdraws from U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Former world number one Boris
Becker has decided on Wednesday not to play in next week's
U.S. Open after the death of his adviser and close friend Axel
Meyer-Woelden.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old German had close personal and business ties
with Meyer-Woelden who died of liver cancer on Monday at 56,
according to sources close to Becker.
</P>
<P>
Becker had been expected to make his final appearance in a
Grand Slam event and make his four-week injury break at the
U.S. Open, which starts in Boston on Monday.
</P>
<P>
His withdrawal means that he may not appear in Grand Slam
tournament any more. And Becker confirmed recently that the end of
his career was nearing.
</P>
<P>
But the former world no. one said he would play a few more
tournaments next year and represents Germany in Davis Cup. 
