<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Quibbling Over Taiwan Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Despite criticism by China, the
Japanese government continues to violate international law by
claiming that an ongoing review of its 1978 defense arrangement
with the U.S. covers the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Japan's Deputy Chief Cabinet
Secretary Kaoru Yosano reiterated the view that new guidelines for
the Japan-U.S. defense cooperation should include handling
emergencies in the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
"Emergencies in surrounding areas, under the guidelines, are
defined in accordance with the nature of the occurrences, not
geographical concepts," the deputy government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
His quibbling echoed remarks by Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku
Kajiyama in a TV interview program on Sunday. During the
interview, Kajiyama said the geographical scope of Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation in areas surrounding Japan should cover the
Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang has made it
clear that China is "seriously concerned" about the remarks made
by Kajiyama, a chief member of the Japanese government. He has
also asked the Japanese government to make "a clear-cut
clarification" on Kajiyama's statement.
</P>
<P>
However, Yosano insisted that "Chief Cabinet Secretary
Kajiyama's remarks are in line with the government stance."
</P>
<P>
Describing Kajiyama's remarks as "indecent and strange,"
Chinese Foreign Vice-Minister Tang Jiaxuan on Tuesday accused
Kajiyama of interfering in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing review of the defense guidelines is designed to
pave the way for Japan to provide a broad range of logistical and
noncombatant support to the U.S. military if an emergency occurs
in areas surrounding Japan.
</P>
<P>
Yosano said the review of the guidelines would not affect
rights and obligations defined by the Japan-U.S. security treaty.
</P>
<P>
"The definition of the Far East under the Japan-U.S. security
treaty will not be changed," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has defined the Far East under the
security treaty as areas from the Philippines to the north,
including Taiwan and the Korean Peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Tie up With ASEAN Fund Managers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
enter into an agreement with fund managers in the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) region to protect the further
depreciation of the country's currency peso.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo today
as he assured the public not to worry about the current financial
situation, according to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo was quoted as saying that the government is doing
everything to normalize the foreign exchange crisis.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to speculations that the exchange rate of the
peso will continue to weaken thus giving stock market speculators
a chance to prop up their activities.
</P>
<P>
But the finance chief did not say whether these speculative
attacks have something to do with the continuing distrust of
foreign investors in the country's economic stability as shown by
the on-going drop in the composite index at the Philippine Stock
Exchange (PSE).
</P>
<P>
Sources at the PSE said that an agreement between fund managers
and the government is expected to provide as a buffer to the
impending attacks on the local currency.
</P>
<P>
At the country's currency market, the peso fell to a record-low
of 30.14 pesos to one U.S. dollar last Friday and appreciated
slightly to 30.03 peso to one dollar today. Monday trading was
suspended because of heavy flooding in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank reportedly will stand firm on its
decision not to intervene in the local currency market in order to
maintain the country's foreign reserve of 10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that the currency crisis will be solved once
remittances from the country's millions of overseas Filipino
workers will start coming in at the end of this quarter in time
for the pre-Christmas season.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
