<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi MPs Tour Uganda for Sanction Lifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Four Burundi parliamentarians
are in Kampala to solicit support for easing sanctions imposed on
their country after an army coup that toppled the elected
government of the former President last year.
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, the MPs led by Frederic
Bamvuginyumvira Tuesday briefed the Parliamentary Committee on
Foreign Affairs and deputy speaker Betty Okwir on the planned
Arusha summit next week at which the parties will have to resolve
their differences on sanctions against Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The summit is scheduled to start on August 25, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Bamvuginyumvira said despite their differences, the Burundi
political parties had decided to work together to find solutions
to their current problems.
</P>
<P>
He also said Uganda's MPs are welcome to Bujumbura to give
advice in the national debate of how to resolve the differences
between political groups there.
</P>
<P>
Karuhanga, Onyango Kakoba and Michael Mukula, all Ugandan MPs
later told the Burundi counterparts that they supported the
lifting of the embargo because it was hurting the ordinary
citizens more than Burundi President Pierre Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
Burundi sank into genocide in 1993 when President Melchoir
Ndadaye was assassinated by Tutsi extremists. More violence
between Tutsis and Hutus erupted after Buyoya ousted President
Ntibatunganya in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, 150,000 people have been killed in the tribal
strife in the country.
</P>
<P>
Trade embargo was subsequently imposed by east and central
African countries like Uganda, Tanzania, Eritrea, Zimbabwe,
Democratic Congo, Kenya, Ethiopia and Zambia as well as the
organization of African Unity (OAU). These countries and the OAU
will be attending the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
