<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Shows Restraint After Rocket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government has
showed restraint towards Tuesday's massive Katyusha rocket attack
on northern Israel by Lebanese Hezbollah guerillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel's "immediate goal is to halt the cycle of escalation
which dose not serve the interests of any side of the border,"
said an official statement issued by the government after the
attack.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that "Israel wants both the citizens of
Israel and Lebanon to live in tranquility."
</P>
<P>
Last night, the entire region of Northern Israel was on
alert. Many residents spent the night in shelters and security
rooms in anticipation of more bombardments, ignoring the
military's advice against the practice.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Defense Ministry has also confirmed that there have
been no unusual military movements in the south.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah fired some 60 Katyusha rockets to northern Israel on
Tuesday morning and the Israel Defense Force (IDF) confirmed that
some 45 landed inside Israel, most of them hit the northern area
of Kiryat Shmona in Galilee, but causing slight casualties.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iran guerrilla force said its attack was in response to
the shelling by the South Lebanese Army (SLA) -- the ally of
Israeli forces stationed in south Lebanon -- of the Lebanese south
port city of Sidon Monday, which killed at least six civilians and
wounded 35 others
</P>
<P>
Following Tuesday's attack, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and several other cabinet members inspected the attacked
areas. Netanyahu said Israel will act to make sure this is not
repeated.
</P>
<P>
Despite the tough talks, the Israeli government's policy is
apparently aimed at winding down the current escalation of tension
by refaining from instant retaliation, observers here said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
