<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Ban Mercenary Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Defense Committee of
South African Parliament is debating a bill to curb mercenary
activities in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The bill was prepared by National Conventional Arms Control
Committee Chairman Kader Asmal.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the bill to parliament, Asmal said mercenary,
military and security type involvement of South Africans abroad
had a direct impact on the country's foreign policy and had to be
controlled.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, bona fides transactions between local
security-type companies and foreign countries would have to be
vetted, and authority granted if the type of activity and
contract country were acceptable to government.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental organizations involved in legitimate conflict
resolution activities would also have to register, but would have
no problem getting the required authority.
</P>
<P>
Military training to democratic countries would be approved on
the payment of a fee which would not be applied to
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, South African mercenaries
took part in armed conflicts in Zaire, Angola and Rwanda during
the past few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
