health personnel for Angola and offer scholarship for demobilized
military men in its peace process, a visiting Cape Verde minister
said today.
</P>
<P>
Joao Medina, Minister for Health, Labor and Social Affairs of
Cape Verde, who arrived here for a week-long visit said Angola
and Cape Verde, which share similar history in fighting against
colonial rule, are striving to raise the level of their
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Although Cape Verde is a small country in terms of land
acreage and population, while Angola is big and rich in natural
resources, the two countries could have effective cooperation in
the social sector, and exchange experiences in this field, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Medina said that Cape Verde could learn from Angola in
afforestation and in its efforts to fight against poverty.
</P>
<P>
As former colonies of Portugal, both states now belong to the
Economic Community of Portuguese-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
The Cape Verde minister said he believed that his visit to
Angola will further promote the brotherly ties of cooperation
between the two countries. 
