<HEADLINE> Lebanese MP: Lebanon Will Continue Confronting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese member of parliament
said today that Lebanese army and resistance forces will continue
confronting Israeli attacks, the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sami el-Khateeb, chairman of the Lebanese Chamber of Deputies'
Defense and Security Committee, was quoted by the radio as saying
that Monday's Israeli attacks on the southern Lebanese city of
Saida are reminiscent of last year's Qena massacre, in which about
100 Lebanese civilians were killed.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Israel of shelling civilians, he said that "under the
plea of security, the Israeli government finds an excuse to go
unbridled."
</P>
<P>
Nine civilians were killed and 43 wounded in fierce shelling
Monday in the southern Lebanese port city of Saida.
</P>
<P>
On April 18, 1996, Israeli gunners shelled a U.N. camp in South
Lebanon. Of the 400 villagers who had sought shelter in the Qena
Camp, 100 were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese official also dismissed Israeli army statement
that the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) in the occupation
zone, not Israeli troops, were behind the attacks.
</P>
<P>
"Blaming the attacks on guerrilla forces of Antoine Lahd is
nonsensical because these forces are instructed by Israel," he
told the radio.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli surrogate South Lebanon Army (SLA), led by Lahd, is
patrolling the occupied border strip in south Lebanon alongside
with the Israeli army, he added.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 Israeli troops have held a border occupation in a
self-declared "security zone" in south Lebanon since 1985, in
defiance of U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
