<HEADLINE> Increased Heilongjiang Grain Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang Province, once a
vast wasteland area, has been transformed into a major grain
producer in northeast China, with this year's spring wheat output
topping 3.64 million tons, up 10.5 percent from the corresponding
1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang's average annual grain output has jumped by 10.5
percent in each of the past seven years, seven percentage points
higher than the national average growth rate.
</P>
<P>
The province's total 1996 grain output of 30.4 million tons was
up 17.5 percent from the previous year and reached the Ninth
Five-Year Plan targets set for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The successful effort has been attributed to the provincial
government priority on the agricultural sector. The local
government had increased the sector's budget by 13.3 percent
annually between 1991 and 1995. The government allocated 1.8
billion yuan to the sector in 1996, an annual increase of 23.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The province's financial sector has introduced preferential
loan for the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang has also attached great importance to water
conservation constructions in order to enhance local resistance to
natural calamities. Heilongjiang invested 2.7 billion yuan in
water conservation projects between 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of scientific farming used in grain production
has jumped 42 percent from 35 percent years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
