<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Alert as Pollution Level Soars in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Health warnings were issued by
experts here today to the public as the air-pollution index has
hit the danger zone.
</P>
<P>
The index, made worse by soaring temperatures and a lack of
wind, reached 109 in new development areas, mostly new towns in
low-lying parts of the "New Territories", on Tuesday, but is
expected to drop below 100 to about 80 today.
</P>
<P>
Anything above 100 is considered "unhealthy" and health
warnings are issued after the index passes 100 points, according
to the air-pollution index from the Environmental Protection
Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Standard newspaper quoted Environmental
Protection Department official Arthur Chu as saying that high
temperatures over the past few days had given rise to the
"unhealthy" pollution index.
</P>
<P>
"The poor air quality we are now experiencing is due to ozone,
which is not directly emitted from pollution sources, but formed
by the reaction of air pollutants in the atmosphere when under
sunlight," Chu said.
</P>
<P>
"The calm and sunny weather over the last few days has provided
sufficient time and the necessary conditions for the polluting
chemicals in the atmosphere to form ozone," Chu added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Environmental Protection Department experts have
advised people with asthma, lung and heart diseases to stay
indoors as much as possible to avoid breathing in chemicals
suspended in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The highest pollution index reading in Hong Kong was 118 on
July 26, 1996, in some industrial areas including Kwun Tong, Kwai
Tsing and Tsuen Wan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
