<HEADLINE> Three More Killed by Floods in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Death toll from flood-related
accidents rose to nine in the flood-stricken northern and central
Philippines as three more have been confirmed dead as of late this
morning, the country's disaster authorities said.
</P>
<P>
In a report sent to President Fidel Ramos, the National
Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said three more, including a
three-year-old child, were drowned and another three more injured
in a landslide and other flood-related accidents.
</P>
<P>
An earlier NDCC report said four drowned, one crushed by a
landslide in Batangas city, and one electrocuted while walking on
a flooded street Tuesday afternoon in Manila. An old man was
injured in the landslide, the only one so far triggered by flash
floods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council said two helicopters and more troops
were dispatched today to help rescue and evacuation operation.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 93,000 families or 475,000 people have been
affected by the widespread flooding, which was caused by
continuing monsoon winds beginning to slash the country since
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Among the affected, the NDCC said more than 21,000 or 111,000
residents living in low-lying areas have been evacuated to 91
makeshift evacuation center set up in churches and public schools.
</P>
<P>
The National Red Cross and the military have extended emergency
food assistance to the evacuees.
</P>
<P>
The worst-hit areas were Metro Manila or the national capital
region, and the provinces of Pampanga and Bulacan around volcanic
Mount Pinatub in central Luzon.
</P>
<P>
Life in the capital city gradually returned to normal today as
continuous downpour turned into occasional moderate rains.
Government offices, schools and businesses reopened today after
being suspended for one day Tuesday in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
But heavy rains are reportedly continuing to fall in other
parts of central Luzon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
