<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Population Quadruples in 38 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A Tibetan scholar has claimed
that the Tibetan population has not decreased since 1959, in fact
it has quadrupled in the past 38 years.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ongoing 1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies,
Tendzin Lhundrub, from the Research Center of Tibetan Studies,
said the belief that the population of the Tibetans was over ten
million in the 7th century was historically groundless and was a
misunderstanding and distortion of historical documents.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the figure might be calculated if the entire
number of the troops during the Tubo period are added, and a
comparison was made between the area and population under the
control of the Tubo regime and the Tibetan area of modern times.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that up to 1959, the total population was about
one million and a large-scale reduction of the Tibetan population
never occurred.
</P>
<P>
"In history, wars, earthquakes and other natural calamities and
epidemic diseases happened many times but the total population
remained unchanged," according to the scholar.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Tibetan population had not been increased, he
added, was determined by material production and social system
in Tibetan society.
</P>
<P>
Religion has played a "regulatory role" in the population
changes, and non-growth in Tibetan population is decided by social
material production and social system in Tibet, he said.
</P>
<P>
A large number of grown-ups and young laborers converged onto
temples to become living Buddhas and religious people, and low
productive forces and poor natural conditions also affected the
population growth in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
However, he went on to say, the Tibetan population has doubled
since 1959, which demonstrates that changes of the Tibetan social
system and the progress and development of productive forces and
improvement of science and medical technology constitute key
factors for population growth in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibetan people have chosen their own road of growth and
are carrying out socialist modernization with Chinese
characteristics. This is the fundamental factor for the steady
population growth," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
