<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenyan Economy Hit by Shilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Over 20 percent drop in the
value of the Kenyan currency of Shilling in the past three weeks
has adversely affected the country's economy with local industry
undermined and commodity prices increased.
</P>
<P>
Manu Chandaria, Chairman of the Kenya Manufacturers
Association, said the depreciation of shilling to the present 71
against the dollar has undermined the local industry as Kenya imports
more than it exports.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the value of imported goods for Kenya
in 1996 is 3 billion U.S. Dollars, compared with exports standing
at 2.1 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"What's worrying to the industry is the sudden fall of the
currency. Had this been gradual over a period of time, it could
have been absorbed," Chandaria noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that local manufacturers had to pass the
increased production cost to consumers as most of the inputs used
in the sector were imported.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan manufactured goods will also become less competitive
because countries with stable currencies can afford to keep down
their prices, the chairman added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the depreciation of Kenyan currency places a higher
burden on the country's ability to serve its external debt.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's debt service stood at 333
billion shillings in March 1997 when the shilling was 54.9 to one
U.S. Dollar, but it has now risen to 437 billion Shillings.
</P>
<P>
At the local market, the wholesale and retail prices of
products have begun to rise following the depreciation of the
shilling against major convertible currencies as a result of the
suspension by the International Monetary Fund of a three-year
loan package to the country on July 31.
</P>
<P>
Mobil, Kenya Shell and BP oil companies have already announced
price increases for the past several days by about eight percent,
which will have a spiral effect on other goods.
</P>
<P>
Staff of the Nakumatt Holdings Ltd., a supermarket chain in
the east African country, said the company had to adjust prices
in response to the shilling depreciation because 50 percent of
their stock was imported.
</P>
<P>
The price of refrigerators went up by 15 percent at Nakumatta
Supermarket while Crown-Berger effected a price rise for various
products effective from August 15 all over the country.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the inflation which had been kept at a single
digit over the past year is expected to rise. Analysts here
noted that the Kenyan government's prediction of 4 percent
economic growth in the 1997/98 fiscal year seems impossible to
realize unless the shilling is stabilized quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
