<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Regulating Commercial Theatrical Performances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The State Council of China has
issued new regulations to improve the management of commercial
theatrical performances.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, which contain 55 articles, stipulate that
performances must adhere to the principle of serving the people
and socialism, and place priority on ensuring appropriate social
effects.
</P>
<P>
The regulations note that the performances should promote the
quality of national arts and enrich the cultural life of the
people. The government will fully support performances targeting
children and rural residents.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, commercial troupes and individual
performers should refrain from unreasonable cancellations of
performances and should strictly avoid cheating audiences in any
manner.
</P>
<P>
The content of advertisements must be both truthful and legal,
and must in no way misguide and deceive consumers. The regulations
clearly stipulate that artists must pay taxes according to law.
</P>
<P>
In addition, organizers and performers should not receive any
portion of income earned from charitable performances.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng has affixed his signature to the regulations
which go into effect on December 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
