<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City To Carry Out "Lifeline Project" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, Guangdong, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Chaozhou, a coastal
city in the eastern part of South China's Guangdong Province, will
carry out a "lifeline project" to protect itself from the threat
of flooding, local authorities announced recently.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to cost a total of 240 million
yuan (about 29 million US dollars), will connect roads along the
southern and northern banks of the Hanjiang River, a major river
flowing by the city, to strengthen the banks and prevent flooding,
according to the city's department of natural disaster prevention.
</P>
<P>
The work is scheduled to be completed within five years. The
first phase, which will soon begin in the fourth quarter of this
year and involves an investment of 63 million yuan, is expected to
end in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
The banks of the Hanjiang River are the second largest in
Guangdong. In recent years they have been repeatedly eroded by
floods, posing a constant danger to the city.
</P>
<P>
Experts warn that the city now faces the threat of the most
serious flooding in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
If the embankments collapse, they said, some three million
people and over one million mu (about 70,000 hectares) of farmland
in Chaozhou and its nearby regions would be affected.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory work for the large project is now underway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Absorbs Foreign Investment for Rising Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's rising industries of
medicine, new materials, micro-electronics, and environmental
protection will become magnets for foreign investment, sources
from the city's economic circles have predicted.
</P>
<P>
According to the city's development program, the annual foreign
contractual value will top 7.5 billion US dollars by the end of
2000, and 4.8 billion US dollars will be used every year. Overseas
investors are encouraged to put more money in the rising
industries.
</P>
<P>
These developing businesses are springing up all over China's
leading economic city, and will play the same important role in
Shanghai's economic development as its six pillar industries --
automobiles, telecommunications, power station, petrochemicals,
iron and steel, and household electric appliances.
</P>
<P>
The annual output value of the modern biology and medicine
industry and the new materials industry have respectively reached
12 billion yuan (1.4 billion US dollars) and nine billion yuan
(1.1 billion US dollars). As forecast, the modern biology and
medicine industry will generate 100 billion yuan (11 billion US
dollars) of the annual output value in next few years, and is
expected to become the city's seventh pillar industry.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai also attracts foreign investment in the fields of
modern agriculture, tourism, foreign trade, education, and science
and technology.
</P>
<P>
So far, Shanghai has more than 16,000 foreign-funded projects,
involving a total of 48 billion US dollars of foreign contractual
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
