<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Sharemarket Closes High After 1,000-point Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index
added 378 points to end at 15,855 today, after a 1,000-point fall
set altogether last Friday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe the rise came partly due to the influence
from Wall Street's rise in currency trading in the past two days
after last weekend's fall.
</P>
<P>
However, the main reason was that Hong Kong's economy is good
and stable and its stock market is perfect, the experts noted.
</P>
<P>
In their view, Hong Kong has a good financial system and has as
much as 80 billion U.S. dollars in its foreign exchange reserves,
and also may rely on the backing of China's huge inland market
and foreign exchange reserves. It is powerful enough to defeat
speculators, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the fall wave, the experts said there was also a
fundamental factor in the slump. Share prices in Hong Kong were on
the upward trend from the beginning of this year, they said,
adding that international speculators may have taken advantages of
this factor to speculate in the Hong Kong dollar and, at the same
time, sell Hong Kong shares.
</P>
<P>
There is no stock market that only rises and never falls, they
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), Tung Chee Hwa, told reporters on Tuesday that the
SAR government would continue to monitor the stock market's
performance.
</P>
<P>
He warned speculators they were certain to lose if they tried
selling the Hong Kong dollar short.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on the same day, Financial Secretary of the SAR
government Donald Tsang Yam-kuen said it was reasonable for Hong
Kong's stock market to adjust after the shares had stood at a high
level for two months.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index rose from 12,000 in April to over
16,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
