<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentally-friendly Dinner-boxes Used on Passenger Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Environmentally-friendly
dinner-boxes are now available in most of China's passenger trains
as part of the effort to combat white pollution caused by the
former widely-used polystyrene containers.
</P>
<P>
China's trains travel along 60,000 kilometers of railways and
carry one billion passengers a year, using over 300 million
dinner-boxes.
</P>
<P>
The polystyrene containers are not easily recycled, and there
have been calls for substitutes made of recyclable and degradable
materials.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, about 95 percent of the passenger trains began to
use dinner-boxes made of degradable materials such as cardboard,
according to the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
In another effort, over 200 million yuan (24.096 million US
dollars) have been spent over the past decade to make it possible
for collecting garbage from trains by bags.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, almost all trains had started the practice,
and garbage disposal stations had been built in 151 of the over
5,000 railway stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
