<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan seeks WEF Grant for Wetlands Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Changsha, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
is seeking a grant from the World Environment Fund to improve
ecological conditions in the east Dongting Lake area.
</P>
<P>
Hunan wants an 18 million US dollars WEF grant to finance four
environmental projects to maintain the diversity of life in the
wetlands.
</P>
<P>
The easternmost section of Dongting Lake, one of China's five
largest freshwater lakes, is home to 216 bird species, including
32 species on the government list of protected animals.
</P>
<P>
Over 10 million birds migrate from the north in winter to the
area, the most extensive wetlands in south China.
</P>
<P>
Local environmental protection officials say WEF funding will
support a project to lower silt levels in the lake and cultivate
grasslands to provide a winter food supply for migrating birds.
</P>
<P>
They also plan to introduce various projects which will enable
local people to earn a living from trades other than fishing, an
activity which currently poses a threat to both wetlands and
wildlife protection.
</P>
<P>
Environmental officials in Hunan, one of many candidates for
WEF funds, have pledged more extensive efforts to ensure
funding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
