<HEADLINE> China Voices Regret for Japanese Officials' Stand on Kajiyama's Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China today expressed deepest
regret for the open support given by some senior Japanese
officials to the recent statement by Japan's Chief Cabinet
Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama concerning the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama clearly indicated in a recent statement that the scope
of the Japan-US security cooperation should include the Taiwan
Straits.
</P>
<P>
Japan's deputy chief cabinet secretary claimed today that the
remarks of Kajiyama reflect the position of the Japanese
government and there is nothing wrong with that. He noted that
some other officials of the Japanese government also supports this
view.
</P>
<P>
Asked by Xinhua to comment on the situation, Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Shen Guofang said today that the remarks of
Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama, a high-ranking member of
the Japanese government, seriously interfere in China's internal
affairs. China had expressed its solemn and just stand to the
Japanese side about this issue.
</P>
<P>
"China is firmly opposed to the statement of Kajiyama and had
asked the Japanese side to make a 'clear-cut clarification' on
Kajiyama's statement," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the Chinese side is "surprised that Japanese
officials concerned even openly support the statement of
Kajiyama." He added that the Chinese side "deeply regrets" this.
</P>
<P>
As everyone knows, Shen reiterated, Taiwan is an inalienable
part of the Chinese territory, and the Taiwan question is purely
China's internal affair. This has become the consensus of the
international community, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side has made solemn commitment and shoulders
political responsibility on this matter in the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement and the Treaty of Peace and Friendship between China and
Japan, Shen added.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side strongly demands that the Japanese side
should strictly carry out its commitments and be consistent in
words and deeds, and refrain from doing anything again that
amounts to interference in China's internal affairs or jeopardizes
the Sino-Japanese relations," the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
