<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Vaccine Could Be Available in 5 Years: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A world-first vaccine which
could prevent breast and other cancers would be available to
general practitioners in five years if tests were successful, one
of its Australian developers said today.
</P>
<P>
"At this stage, where it would be available for practicing
doctors, I would say it will be a minimum of three to five years,"
said Professor Ian McKenzie of the Austin Research Institute in
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
While the vaccine was not a cure and he did not want to be
prematurely optimistic, the professor said trials beginning in
Melbourne this month were an important step towards eradicating
many cancers.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to be optimistic," he was quoted today by the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We're starting these trials and the trial by definition is to
find out if it's any good or not.
</P>
<P>
"If the trial ... is non-toxic and in response the tumors do
shrink away, we can then have another conference and tell you it's
the best thing this century."
</P>
<P>
The trials would be performed on breast cancer sufferers, or
those with colon, rectal and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine, initially tested on mice and then on 25 advanced
breast cancer patients in the state of Queensland, northeast
Australia, last year, did not have side effects and did cause
tumor shrinkage, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
The Melbourne trials, which will start with colon and rectal
cancer patients in the next two weeks, involving 20 patients
overall, will be conducted on advanced cancer sufferers.
</P>
<P>
Paul Mitchell, director of cancer services at the institute,
said the trials would concentrate more on tumor shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine is designed to work in the same way a tetanus or
the successful smallpox vaccine worked, by creating an immune
response in the body to a synthetic antigen.
</P>
<P>
In this case a synthetic form of mucin, a substance found on
cancer cells, is injected into patients, stimulating the white
cells to fight and kill cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Vasso Apostolopoulos, one of the developers, made the
breakthrough discovery to coat the synthetic cancer in sugar,
which stimulates the immune response, as part of her Ph.D.
studies.
</P>
<P>
Professor McKenzie said plans were underway for similar trials
to be conducted in Greece.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
