<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks to Resume Lending to Thai Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks with branches in
Thailand have agreed to resume extending credit to Thai companies
and roll over the existing loans, a senior Thai official said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new movement was reported by local media after Bank of
Thailand governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi met with representatives
of the Foreign Bankers' Association in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
However, Chaiyawat did not make further comment on any
conditions that might be attached to new loans or the terms of
rolling over the current debts.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign bank branches in Thailand a few months ago froze
their Thai credit due to currency and default risks and the
problems facing the country's finance sector.
</P>
<P>
David Proctor, chairman of the association, said that the group
was confident that Thailand's economy will improve under the
International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s rescue package.
</P>
<P>
The association will fully support the IMF rescue plan, which
will help in restructuring and developing Thailand's financial
system, Proctor said.
</P>
<P>
Association members had agreed to comply with the Thai central
bank's new requirement to raise their contribution to its
financial institutions development fund, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, foreign banks' total outstanding loans to Thailand's
91 finance firms stood at 5 billion U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
So far, 19 foreign banks have opened their branch in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank earlier had required foreign bank
branches, which saw a rising inflow of deposits after the bank
suspended extra 42 finance firms on August 5, to raise their
contribution to the fund as a measure to protect local small banks
from collapsing due to the withdrawal panic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
