<HEADLINE> Nigeria Continues Fuel Importation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will continue to import
fuel after September, when the current import package expires, a
senior industry official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ahaji Haruna Abubakar, the Managing Director of the Pipelines
and Products Marketing Company (PPMC) said this is necessary for
the country to build up a reasonable reserve.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's short-term target is to have a 20-day reserve, while
the long-term target is a 45-day reserve, according to managing
director.
</P>
<P>
An acute fuel shortage forced Nigeria, the world's major oil
producer, to order for 33 cargoes of petroleum products in July.
</P>
<P>
The import has successfully eliminated fuel scarcity in major
cities like Lagos, Warri, Port-Harcourt and Suleja, said
Abubakar, adding that the company now now has a 10-day reserve of
petrol, 18 days of dried oil, 19 of aviation kerosene and 14 of
domestic kerosene.
</P>
<P>
Extremely improper national reserve is widely held responsible
for the country's constant fuel scarcity, besides the poor
performance of its four refineries.
</P>
<P>
In a latest development, the government has contracted TOTAL,
the French oil firm to repair and manage the Kaduna Refinery for
three years, a major progress in revitalizing the refineries.
</P>
</TEXT>
