<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Language Continues to Flourish: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A Tibetan educational expert has
cited the Tibetan still as the common language in the
Tibetan-inhabited regions and said that it continues to flourish.
</P>
<P>
In a paper submitted to the 1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan
Studies which opened here today, Changngupa Dorje Ngodrub, deputy
director of the Education Commission of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, said that the Tibetan language was taught in the 1950s as
the part of the main curriculum at primary schools set up by the
Chinese government in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Lhasa Middle School, founded in 1956, and
other middle schools taught mathematics, physics and chemistry in
Tibetan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the reform and opening-up was launched in the late 1970s,
the work of teaching in Tibetan has been reinforced, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Now in Tibet, primary schools, middle schools, secondary
professional schools, as well as universities and colleges all
offer Tibetan language as a required course. Special textbooks
have been written for these classes, he added.
</P>
<P>
And universities in the Tibet autonomous region and other
provinces have been responsible for training Tibetan language
teachers, he said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that Tibetan language has the advantage of
being less of a burden for teachers and students, as it is easier
for them to understand and better teaching results can be
achieved. The language is especially welcomed by children of the
farmers and herdsmen, who constitute 80 percent of the students.
</P>
<P>
He went on say that the Tibetan language is now the
indispensable instrument used by the Tibetan people to exchange
ideas and develop their culture and education.
</P>
<P>
"Tibetan has been used for a long period of time already and is
still in use in Tibet," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
