<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunken Warships Discovered in Northeast China Province (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The warship Jingyuan, which
sank in a fierce battle against Japanese imperialists 103 years
ago, has been discovered 10 miles from the Heidao Island in the
Yellow Sea in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sites where three other battleships sank, the
Zhiyuan, the flagship headed by Deng Shichang, a national hero,
together with two other smaller ships, Chaoyong and Yangwei, have
been located in an area between Dalu Island and Heidao (Black)
Island after a three-month investigation.
</P>
<P>
During the 1894-1895 Sino-Japanese War, the four Chinese
warships fought a five-hour bloody battle against the Japanese
invaders in the Huanghai Sea. All of the vessels sank on
September, 17, 1894.
</P>
<P>
Famed Chinese salvage expert Zhang Zhiqui, who is also the top
official of the headquarters of warship salvage, told Xinhua that
the Jingyuan is now only an empty hull, as the Japanese had
dismantled the warship along with three others in 1939.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that "the sunken ships still could be used as
a good patriotism 'textbook' full of historical evidence to teach
young people to remember the national disgrace."
</P>
<P>
Salvage workers found that the bow and stern of the Jingyuan
are buried deep under the seabed. The parts of the boat sticking
out stand only 0.5 meters high above seabed and are covered with
marine organisms. The ship is 17 meters below sea level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunken Warships Discovered in Northeast China Province (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Military experts here said that Lin Yongsheng, captain of
"Jingyuan" was a wise and capable commander. When the warship was
torpedoed by the Japanese, Li chose to sink the ship in the area
just offshore where it could avoid further pounding from the
Japanese artillery and sailors would be safe.
</P>
<P>
They said his choice was the most rational under those
conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, 16 sailors from the downed
ship survived, though Lin and hundreds of other soldiers died in
the battle.
</P>
<P>
Divers have found a round iron casting that looks like an air
passageway from the Jingyuan, which might have been used by
sailors.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the Jingyuan weighed 2,900
tons and the Zhiyuan, 2,300 tons. The Jingyuan was made in Germany
and the other three warships were made in Britain. They were
modern vessels in their day and carried dozens of big guns.
</P>
<P>
Li Guiben, an 84-year-old eyewitness to the battle, said in
1938 he was forced by the Japanese to help destroy the sunken
ships. Nearly 60 years later, he guided the salvage workers to the
sites.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said China began in May to search for the four warships
using submarine sonar, magnetic detectors and other advanced
technology.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that after the four warships are
salvaged, they will be put into a memorial hall, to be built in
the city of Donggang in Liaoning Province, which will be funded by
the central government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
