<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Israeli exports to Jordan were estimated at 6.75
million U.S. dollars in the first half of this year, while the
Jordanian exports to Israel reached 6.12 million dollars over the
same period, semi-official Jordan Times today quoted a statement
from the Israeli Embassy in Jordan as saying.
</P>
<P>
This is a reflection of the steady flow of cross-border trade
between the two countries despite a setback in the Middle East
peace process, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good start, but not the whole potential," said
Shaul Sasson, commercial attache at the Israeli Embassy in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's main imports from Israel were machinery, chemicals
and other goods used in joint Israeli-Jordanian ventures, while
its main exports to Israel were textiles, air conditioning
machinery, pharmaceutics, foodstuffs and agricultural goods.
</P>
<P>
A peace treaty was signed between the two countries in 1994
after a 46-year state of war between them, but cross-border trade
only began in mid-1996, when they reached a transport accord.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government signed a contract of 4.4
million U.S. dollars with two local companies on Tuesday to
develop infrastructure construction on the eastern coast of the
Dead Sea.
</P>
<P>
The contract stipulates that the two firms, the Zakariya
Tarawneh Contractors and the Cooperative Contracting Company,
should build roads and drainage canals in an area where hotels and
water, electricity and telephone networks are to be constructed,
semi-official Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Minister of Water and Irrigation
Munther Haddadin affirmed that the Jordan Valley Authority (JVA),
responsible for developing the Valley, has intensified efforts to
attract investments to develop the tourists facilities near the
Dead Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Dead Sea is one of the notable tourist spot in Jordan as
well as in the world. It attracts millions of visitors every year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Some 25 Egyptian companies for foodstuff, meat and
dairy products will participate in the biggest food industries
exhibition "Anoga 97" to be held in Cologne, Germany, on October
11-16, the Egyptian economic weekly Middle East News issued
Tuesday reported.
</P>
<P>
Products of more than 6,000 producers representing 100
countries will be displayed at the exhibition, which includes 10
departments and is considered the biggest international exhibition
in this field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
