<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Restates Military Option in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Sani Abacha has restated the stand of the west African sub-region
to use force as the last option to flush out the military junta
in Sierra Leone which seized power in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
However, the action would depend on whether the junta should
maintain its belligerent position by not acceding to popular
global demand that it return power to the toppled civilian
government, Abacha noted.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, who is also the current Chairman of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), made the remarks on
Tuesday in the capital Abuja on his just-concluded visit to Cote
d'Ivoire and Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The position of the sub-region was supported by the United
Nations and the Organization of African Unity, he said.
</P>
<P>
While refusing to say if military action would come soon,
Abacha said that ECOWAS heads of state would have to "consult and
coordinate".
</P>
<P>
But clearly "we have wasted a lot of time," he noted.
</P>
<P>
A summit of ECOWAS heads of state is scheduled for next week
in Abuja. The crisis in Sierra Leone is believed to be high on
the agenda of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The issue was also the focus of his one-day trip on Monday to
Cote d'Ivoire and Guinea. Both countries have been working
closely together with Nigeria and Ghana in the ECOWAS committee
of four on Sierra Leone, which was set up in the wake of the
coup.
</P>
<P>
The committee has held two rounds of talks with
representatives of the junta. Sanctions against the troubled
country have been tightened, but the efforts have not yielded any
fruit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
