<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 130 Rebels Killed in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 130 Tamil rebels were
killed and another 200 more injured in a fierce fighting Tuesday
with government troops, who resumed their campaign on the rebel
northern stronghold of Puliyankulam town, military sources here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the troops met stiff resistance from the
rebels east of Puliyankulam as they advanced northward from
earlier-held positions.
</P>
<P>
The troops engaged the rebels with artillery, tanks, aircraft
and helicopter gunships, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Two buses carrying rebel reinforcements were completely
destroyed by the government troops in an ambush southwest of
Puliyankulam.
</P>
<P>
A total of 29 government soldiers were killed, as well as six
officers and another 58 soldiers were injured during the
confrontation, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Three battle tanks of the troops were damaged by rebels' fire
east of Puliyankulam.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the maneuver of battle tanks was limited on
the eastern flank of the town as the rebels had dug many ditches
and set up other obstacles.
</P>
<P>
By afternoon the troops commenced consolidating the
newly-captured areas after forcing the rebels to move further
northward.
</P>
<P>
The troops were within one kilometer from Puliyankulam, 220
kilometers north of the capital Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The troops launched the campaign on the town in an effort to
capture the highway that links the government-held Vavuniya to
Kilinochchi further north, a vital supply route to the north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
