<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The total trade of Singapore
grew by 7 percent in July on a three-month moving average basis,
reflecting increases in both exports and imports, the Singapore
Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
On a three-month moving average basis, the TDB said that
non-oil domestic exports increased by 4.8 percent while re-exports
increased by 7.9 percent. Oil exports recorded moderate growth of
5.7 percent, while imports increased by 7.8 percent in July this
year.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, however, non-oil domestic exports increased
by 6.9 percent, lower than the 8.8 percent growth registered in
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
In particular, domestic exports of electronics and related
products recorded a moderate growth of 5.4 percent following a 7.6
percent increase in June.
</P>
<P>
The TDB noted that the growth performance within the
electronics industry was uneven. While domestic exports of
integrated circuits, disk drives and printed circuits boards
assembled continued to grow, domestic exports of personal
computers and computer peripherals were weak.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports increased steadily by 7.1 percent in the month, due
mainly to demand for electronics from the United States and the
European Union, it said.
</P>
<P>
Imports rose by 11.4 percent in the month, marking the highest
growth since April 1996.
</P>
<P>
The TDB said that this was partly boosted by imports of ships
and aircraft. Excluding lumpy items such as ships and aircraft,
import growth was 9.4 percent in July, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
