<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Posts and Telecommunications More Available (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of telephones
available to every 100 Chinese people had increased from one in 1991
to six by the end of last year, while for city residents the figure
leaped to 22.4.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the business volume of posts and
telecommunications enjoyed an average growth of 45.7 percent
annually, with a total of 337.4 billion yuan of investment in
fixed assets, 16.7 times that of the previous six years combined,
according to a report recently released by the State Statistical
Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
A 130,000-km nationwide fiber optical network now links all the
capital cities and major coastal cities, with the exception of
Lhasa. Another two inter-provincial expressway postal routes have
been added, as well as a water mail route along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The country had a total switching capacity of 109 million
telephone lines at the end of last year, a more than quadruple
increase over five years ago, to rank third in the world.
</P>
<P>
China's telecommunications network is now dominated by
program-controlled exchange, fiber optics, digital microwave,
satellites, mobile and digital communication, and transformed from
man-made into automatic operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Posts and Telecommunications More Available (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consequently, the network has advanced from using simulated
technology to digital technology, with a simulated network roaming
nationwide, and a digital network connecting 15 provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities. The digital network covers
prefectural-level cities, most of the counties and part of
townships.
</P>
<P>
The total number of telephone subscribers has expanded to 54.9
million, that of pager users to nearly 30 million, and mobile
phone users have topped 10 million to become one of the world's
largest mobile phone networks, the SSB report said.
</P>
<P>
As China's market economy grows, there have been emerging
commodity markets, financial and stock markets, as well as markets
for technology, labor service and information. All these not only
exerted great pressure on the formerly-lagging posts and
telecommunications, but also opened unprecedented business
opportunities for the sector.
</P>
<P>
The sector has markedly improved its structure during the
period. Telecommunications service volume rose from 71.8 percent
in 1991 to 88.2 percent at the end of 1996, whereas mail service
volume dropped from 28.2 percent to 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the establishment of China Unicom has ended the
monopolization of the sector. And it is believed that competition
will certainly help push China's telecommunications onto the
market, and meet the needs of national economic development.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the sector has reported a qualitative
leap in business scale, technological improvements, and service
standards, creating a grand achievement not only in the history of
China's posts and telecommunications, but also in the world's, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
