<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi MPs Seek Uganda's Support for Lifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) --Four Burundi parliamentarians
who are on a visit here, will solicit support for the easing of
sanctions imposed on Burundi after an army coup that toppled the
elected President Slvestre Mibalunganya in July last year.
</P>
<P>
According to local mass media today, the Burundian MPs led by
Frederic Bamvuginyumvira Tuesday briefed the Ugandan
parliamentary committee on foreign affairs on the planned
all-party Burundian conference scheduled for August 25 in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Bamvuginyumvira said that despite differences among the
Burundian parties, the parties had decided to work together to
find solutions to the problems facing in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that Uganda's MPs are welcome to Bujumbura to give
advice in the national debate of how to resolve differences
between political groups there.
</P>
<P>
Burundi sank into genocide in 1993 when President Melchior
Ndadaye was assassinated by Tutsi extremists. More violence
between Tutsis and Hutus erupted after Major Pierre Buyoya ousted
President Ntibatunganya in July last year. About 150,000 people
have been killed since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions have been imposed last year by neighboring African
states against the military regime in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Countries supporting the embargo namely Uganda, Tanzania,
Eritrea, Zimbabwe, Democratic Republic of Congo, Kenya, Ethiopia
and Zambia as well as the Organisation of African Unity will
attend the Arusha conference on Burundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
