<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Sells 111 State Firms in Past 12 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 111 state-owned
companies privatized between July 1, 1996 and July 31 this year
have been sold for 137.65 billion Kwacha (about 106 million U.S.
Dollars), according to the latest report from the Zambia
Privatization Agency (ZPA).
</P>
<P>
The report says 208 parastatal companies have so far been
privatized, 40 are under negotiations, 33 are in the process of
being sold, 25 are lined up for possible liquidation or asset
sale and 11 are not handled by ZPA.
</P>
<P>
One company is under pre-privatization, eight firms face the
fate of litigation, injunctions or receiverships, bringing the
total working portfolio to 306 companies, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that 68 companies were sold in local currency
amounting to some 23.4 billion Kwacha, 40 sold in about 106
million U.S. Dollars, and 10 sold in South African currency at
about 21 million Rand.
</P>
<P>
Zambia embarked on its privatization process in 1992, soon
after the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) took
over power in the elections held in late 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
