<HEADLINE> Olympic Fever Running High in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic fever is
mounting in Cape Town when people in the South African capital
are waiting for September 5, the date when the International
Olympic Committee will announce the successful bidder of the 2004
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources reaching here said today that recent
indications of Cape Town's improved chances have helped stir
popular sentiment, which is echoed by mounting support throughout
Africa.
</P>
<P>
With a little help from the fire brigade, they said, the Cape
Town Chamber of Commerce and Industry raised a big banner at its
foreshore headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Chamber President Ali Gierdien noted, "Now's time to show our
support."
</P>
<P>
He appealed to businesses across the peninsula to follow suit
by using bid regalia, posters and banners to dress their
premises, and encouraging staff to wear yellow ribbons to show
their support.
</P>
<P>
This is a prelude to a week-long festivities starting from
tomorrow to provide a rousing send-off to the bid team, which
leaves for Lausanne, Switzerland next weekend.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said earlier that he
would visit Lausanne early next month to be on hand for Olympic
Games bid result. 
</P>
