<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Kenya's constitutional reforms talks between the
government and opposition set for August 20 have been put off,
simmering the political tension ahead of the general elections in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"After necessary consultations, it has been decided that the
launching of negotiation scheduled for tomorrow at Safari Park
Hotel be postponed until further notice," said spokesman of the
mediation committee Mutava Musyimi Tuesday. (Kenya-Reform Talks)
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The building of two light-water nuclear reactors in
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) will serve as a
catalyst in promoting exchanges between the two sides on the
Korean Peninsula, observers here say.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's ground-breaking ceremony for the two 1,000-megawatt
nuclear reactors in Sinpo, South Hamgyong Province, DPRK, signaled
the conclusion of the nearly three year-long efforts to get the
1994 Geneva nuclear accord underway. (South Korea-DPRK-Reactors)
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Chief justices and justice ministers from Asia and
Pacific will gather here for a roundtable meeting next Monday to
discuss legal and judicial reforms in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) announced today that the
meeting will discuss principal trends in legal and judicial
reforms in ADB members and will relate these to the bank's
technical assistance to its members for such reforms.
(Philippines-Justice Ministers)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Teamsters union's 50-member national
negotiating committee and the Teamsters panel of local
representatives Tuesday voted unanimously to ratify a tentative
contract reached Monday with the United Parcel Service (UPS).
</P>
<P>
Teamsters President Ron Carey said the offer would now be
mailed to the 185,000 union members to be ratified.
</P>
<P>
Teamsters were reportedly getting ready to return to work after
the tentative agreement was reached. (US-UPS-Accord)
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- More than 30,000 Cambodian refugees have fled into
southeastern Thailand due to recent attacks launched by Cambodian
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen's forces against those loyal to
Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees, carrying possessions on bicycles,
motorcycles and carts, streamed into southeastern Thailand's Surin
 province through Chong Chom pass in Dap Choeng district, local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities and non-government organizations were
providing food and medical services to the refugees.
(Thailand-Cambodia-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Parliament leader of Bosnia's Serb Republic, Dragan
Kalinic, Tuesday urged Bosnian Serb leaders to stop infighting,
the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Serb Republic is facing a huge danger with the
intensification of infighting among the Serb leadership, Kalinic
said in a public rally in Doboj, about 100 kilometers north of
Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the Serbs could lose control of the strategic
town of Brcko in the coming elections if the infighting does not
come to a halt immediately. (Bosnia-Serbs-Infighting)
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin pledged
Tuesday that the murderer of a deputy mayor would not be allowed
to remain at large.
</P>
<P>
Mikhail Manevich, 36, deputy mayor and chairman of the State
Property Committee of St. Petersburg, was attacked early Monday on
his way to work. He died later. (Russia-Murder-Investigation)
</P>
<P>
BONN -- A leader of Turkey's militant separatist group Kurdish
Workers Party (PKK) has declared an unconditional renunciation of
violence in Germany, said German television reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Germany's ZDF television network, PKK
leader Abdullah Oczalan said that the past violence by the PKK in
Germany had been wrong. (Germany-Turkey-Violence) 
</P>
