<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in Zambia Likely to Rise Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The inflaion rate which has been
declining steadily in Zambia in the last few months is likely to rise
in the later part of the year due to the recent price increases of
some commodities.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Zambia Association of Chambers of Commerce and
Industry (ZACCI) indicates that the inflation rate which is currently
at 23 percent will rise due to the recent price increases of some
commodities such as fuel, electricity and water tariffs, combined with
the expected massive importation of expensive maize from outside
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The economic report for the second quarter says the government
recorded a significant fiscal budget surplus of 41.8 billion Kwacha
(about 32 million U.S.Dollars) for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The surplus is mainly attributed to tremendous improvements in the
collection of import Value Added Tax (VAT) which in the first quarter
was on the decline at 25.6 billion Kwacha (about 20 million dollars)
compared to 32.2 billion Kwacha (about 24.6 million Dollars) collected
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Collections in other areas such as customs duty, excise duty,
domestic VAT, fees and fines also show dramatic increases in the
second quarter, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
