<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Businessmen Blast Nation's Economic Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's leading business
leaders have criticized the country's overall economic condition,
law and order, saying it had become increasingly difficult for
them to pursue normal business and industrial activities.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of some leading chamber and trade bodies in a joint
statement on Tuesday also urged the government to dispassionately
review the economic situation as well as law and order.
</P>
<P>
"Take necessary corrective measures before the economic
deterioration goes beyond control," said those disappointed
business leaders, who are from the Metropolitan Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, the Foreign Investors Chamber of Commerce
and Industry, the Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters
Association and some other major bodies.
</P>
<P>
According to them, the macro-economic fundamentals are under
pressure, which has already threatened investment climate, upset
trade and industry. If the trend continues, it will be impossible
to achieve this year's envisaged growth rate of 7 percent, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The worried business leaders urged the government to contain
liquidity crisis in the banks, stop alarming fall in the foreign
exchange reserve and break stalemate in the export sector, which
is the locomotive of this country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Tight monetary policy, liquidity problems in the banks arising
from large-scale borrowings by the government and the state-owned
enterprises have brought about a near stalemate in financing new
investments," they observed.
</P>
<P>
They urged the government to check manifold increase in
smuggled goods on the market, curb decline in the prices of crops
and retrieve the collapsing stock market.
</P>
<P>
These problems, they said, coupled with energy shortages and
unbelievable harassment of business people by local hoodlums, make
it difficult to run normal business activities.
</P>
<P>
They complained that till date there was no indication that the
earlier assurance of the energy minister to solve the power
problem after September this year would come true.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
