<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Has More College Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Eighty prestigious Chinese
universities have awarded college degrees to nearly 8,000 students
from southwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Highly prestigious universities, including Beijing University,
Qinghua University and Nanjing University, have provided the
region with more than 7,000 undergraduates, according to
information released during a recent conference on coordinating
higher education.
</P>
<P>
In addition, various colleges and universities have awarded
numerous advanced degrees and some 300 foreign language teachers
have also completed training programs offered by centers in other
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The universities have also trained 600 ethnic minority cadres
and business managers to meet the needs of local economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Since 1989, the State Education Commission, the State
Nationalities Affairs Commission and the Xinjiang government have
jointly sponsored a program to train more talented members of
ethnic minority groups. In addition, dozens of prestigious
universities have offered special classes for ethnic minority
students and have reduced annual tuition fees. 
</P>
