<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Tibetan Studies Seminar (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Some 130 scholars from both at
home and abroad are attending a four-day seminar on Tibetan
studies which opened today at the China Tibetology Research Center
(CTRC) in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The scholars came from a dozen countries and regions
including China, Russia, Britain, India, the United States,
Switzerland, Australia, Nepal, Japan, New Zealand, Germany,
Canada, and China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and
Taiwan region.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Chinese scholars are attending the seminar which
has attracted over 100 papers.
</P>
<P>
The "1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies" follows similar
seminars held in Lhasa and Beijing in 1986 and 1991, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan studies involve research related to the society and
culture of the Tibetan ethnic group which inhabits the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau known as the "roof of the world" in
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan studies also cover the ethnic group's written and
spoken language, as well as history, philosophy, religion,
literature, arts and folklore in the category of human studies;
politics and economic in the social sciences; and Tibetan
medicine, astronomy, geography, architecture and natural sciences.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibetan ethnic group is one of the outstanding members of
the big family of the Chinese nation, and the Tibetan people have
used their diligence and wisdom to create a culture which bears
its own unique characteristics," according to CTRC
Director-General Doje Cedain.
</P>
<P>
Doje told participants attending today's opening session that
the remarkable Tibetan culture has synthesized the outstanding
achievements of cultures and long history of the Han and various
other ethnic groups. Tibetans are an organic component of the
Chinese civilization and have contributed greatly to world
civilization.
</P>
<P>
"The central government cares greatly about the social,
economic and cultural development of the Tibet Autonomous Region,
and has adopted a series of favorable policies promoting economic
development in the region," said Doje.
</P>
<P>
He said The central government, which encourages and has
provided great support for studies of the fine traditional culture
in Tibet, has allocated substantial funding to train research
personnel and establishing research institutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
