<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Tibetan Studies Seminar (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show that well over 2,000 researchers work in the
nation's more than 50 institutions engaged in Tibetan studies.
</P>
<P>
Six Chinese and foreign scholars delivered speeches at the
plenary meeting today. They noted that the Tibetan people
have learned from one another and from the Han people and members
of other ethnic groups for hundreds of years, with the combined
efforts leading to the creation of Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
The harsh natural environment on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and
the characteristics of Tibetan society have formed a culture with
very distinct features. Tibetan studies originated in China and
have attracted the great attention of both Chinese and foreign
scholars.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Tibetan writing was introduced in the seventh
century has yielded a wealth of ancient books and records in the
Tibetan language, as well as voluminous historical records about
the Tibetan society in the Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
Related research led to the formation of Tibetan studies. The
care and support of the Communist Party and the government over
the past four decades since the peaceful liberation of Tibet have
led to marked progress in Tibetan studies throughout China.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, publishing houses across the country have
published a large number of academic monographs and reference
books in both the Tibetan and Chinese languages.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bibliography on Tibetan Studies in China, was
published by the Foreign Languages Press, 1,497 kinds of books
were published in China between 1949-1992. According to recent
estimates, nearly 1,000 books on Tibetan studies have been
published since 1992.
</P>
<P>
In addition, research institutions on Tibetology are providing
numerous periodicals.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 12-odd years, Tibetan studies have been closely
linked with the social, economic and cultural development in areas
inhabited by people of Tibetan ethnic group, including the Tibet
Autonomous Region and Sichuan, Qinghai, Gansu and Yunnan
provinces. Related efforts have helped to promote local reform,
opening to the outside world and modernization.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars have played an active role in expanding
academic exchanges with their counterparts abroad, and have
translated many important works by foreign specialists.
</P>
<P>
Publishing houses are sponsoring an exhibition, providing
seminar participants with access to Tibetan studies books in the
Tibetan, Chinese, English, German and French languages.
</P>
<P>
The CTRC and the Social Academy of Tibet Autonomous Region are
sponsoring the seminar, which will be followed by fact-finding
tour of Tibet by a group of foreign scholars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
