<HEADLINE> Kenya's Reform Talks Put off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's constitutional reforms
talks between the government and the opposition set for August 20
have been put off suddenly, simmering the political tension ahead
of the general elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
"After necessary consultations, it has been decided that the
launching of negotiation scheduled for tomorrow (today) at Safari
Park Hotel be postponed until further notice," said spokesman of
the mediation committee Mutava Musyimi last night.
</P>
<P>
He gave no reasons for the postponement, which came hours
after a meeting by the parliamental group of ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) over the talks.
</P>
<P>
Tthe KANU lawmakers announced Tuesday their party will only
hold talks within the legislative framework, though a 37-member
KANU negotiation team has been formed.
</P>
<P>
It indicated that the KANU will not enter into any talks with
the opposition umbrella body National Convention Executive
Council (NCEC), set up in April to coordinate the opposition's
campaign for the constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC itself named a 50-member team of its representatives
to the mediation talks last Thursday. The NCEC team composed
representatives from all political parties and other interest
groups.
</P>
<P>
However, a row on the NCEC nomination sparked Tuesday After
the main opposition FORD-Kenya removed its parliamental members
James Orengo and Otieno K'Opiyo as representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
