<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tourists Visit Huangshan Mountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Over two million tourists visited
the Huangshan Mountains, a well-known scenic spot in east China's
Anhui Province, in the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a nearly 68 percent jump from the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 114,400 overseas tourists represented a substantial rise of
132 percent.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from domestic tourism hit 261 million yuan (31.45
million US dollars), up 46.6 percent, and those from overseas
tourists shot up 77 percent to 21 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Huangshan Mountains are best known for peaks shrouded by
clouds, unusual rock formations and unique pine trees. The
mountains, considered one of the most picturesque mountains in
China, are on the World Natural and Cultural Heritages Lists of
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Local tourism authorities attributed the surge in visitors to
the opening of air routes linking the mountains with other major
tourism cities throughout the country and the recent introduction
of direct train services to big cities of Shanghai and Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
Last year's successful listing of the Huangshan Tourism
Development Co. Ltd. on the domestic stock market has helped to
improve Huangshan's reputation and has been a major factor
contributing to growth in the area's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Local officials have tried to provide a better environment by
launching an extensive campaign to eradicate malpractices such as
tourist guides soliciting kickbacks, high-pressure selling, and
restaurants earning excessive profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
