<HEADLINE> Japanese Arrested for Ship Fraud in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Police have arrested a Japanese
national for allegedly selling a non-existing
17-million-peso-worth of cargo ship to a Filipino shipping
magnate, police said here today.
</P>
<P>
Police said that they placed under custodial investigation
Tuesday Masaru Igawa, 59, who introduced himself as a businessman
of 727 Higashi, Shizuoka Ken, Japan, upon complaint filed by Felix
Pontino, a rich trader in the city of General Santos, the Southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Police said Igawa agreed to sell to Pontino on May 23 this year
a ship for 17 million pesos (about 1.2 million U.S. dollars) and
Pontino initially paid Igawa 15.6 million pesos (570,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The rest of the total amount was paid by five separate down
payments before August 4, police said.
</P>
<P>
Pontino, to make sure, secretly went to Japan to verify Igawa's
credibility early this month but found it was a fraud, according
to the police.
</P>
<P>
Police said that Igawa was detained at the Western Police
District Headquarters in Manila and will be charged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
