<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Leads China in Tea Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Most residents in Shanghai,
China's largest manufacturing center, still prefer hot tea despite
the growing popularity of cold beverages.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that Shanghai residents consume more than
seven million kg of tea annually, with the city's per capita
consumption of 0.55 kg surpassing the national average by 74
percent.
</P>
<P>
Tea is the preferred drink for almost 88 percent of the city's
residents, with 37.5 percent preferring hot tea even on the
hottest summer days.
</P>
<P>
Tea shops line Shanghai's bustling streets and lanes, with most
large department stores offering tea counters..
</P>
<P>
The city is home to more than 4,000 tea shops, with the
Shanghai Zhejiang Tea Co. operating 16 chain stores and
counters. The tea wholesale market on the Dadong Street serves as a
major tea distribution center in the city.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai residents are well versed in tea culture. The city has
held the Shanghai International Tea Culture Festival four times,
and the Shanghai Tea Association holds nearly 100 lectures
annually on the tea culture. The city's 12 teahouses have gained
great popularity with local residents.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 primary and middle school students have
shown their great interest in tea culture by organizing tea
culture groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
