<HEADLINE> Fuel Price Hike Sparks Strong Protest in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The price hike of petroleum
products has triggered sharp reactions among different political
parties and transport circles while the main opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) threatened a nation-wide strike on August
24.
</P>
<P>
BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia Tuesday urged the government to
withdraw the decision, saying that a country-wide dawn-to-dusk
strike will be observed on August 24 if the fuel prices are not
lowered by August 23.
</P>
<P>
From Tuesday, the petrol price rose sharply to 21 taka (about
0.47 U.S. dollars) from 13.70 taka (about 0.31 dollars) after the
government refixed the prices of all petroleum products in a bid
to keep pace with the international market.
</P>
<P>
This move, however, touched off strong protests in the country.
On Tuesday, the owners and workers of motor tricycles, a major
transport means in Bangladesh, went on a wildcat strike in the
capital Dhaka and the second-largest city Chittagong.
</P>
<P>
The angry motor tricycle drivers announced that they would go
for a greater movement if the government did not withdraw the
enhanced prices by August 25.
</P>
<P>
Even the two partners of the present government, the Jatiya
(national) Party and the JSD (Rab), also expressed concern over
the price hike of the petroleum products, saying the government
should immediately withdraw the new prices.
</P>
<P>
The Jatiya Party chief, former president H. E. Ershad said in a
statement Tuesday that the abrupt price rise would increase the
cost of essential commodities resulting in high prices of all
goods.
</P>
<P>
Ershad said the increase in fuel prices would also have a
negative impact on the national economy and urged the government
to refix the fuel price as before.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Petroleum Corporation, the lone importer of
petroleum products, proposed to raise the petroleum prices in
early June, arguing that a loss of 5 billion taka (about 112
million dollars) has occurred due to the higher prices on the
international oil market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the donor countries and agencies including the World
Bank have been pressing the government hard to stop the huge
subsidy in the petroleum sector by raising the petroleum prices.
</P>
<P>
The price structure of widely-used petroleum products was
framed six years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
