<HEADLINE> Teamsters Leaders Ratify Tentative Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Teamsters union's
50-member national negotiating committee and the Teamsters panel
of local representatives today voted unanimously, on separate
occasions, to ratify a tentative contract reached late Monday
night with the United Parcel Service (UPS).
</P>
<P>
Teamsters President Ron Carey said the offer would now be
mailed to the 185,000 union members to be ratified.
</P>
<P>
Teamsters were reportedly getting ready to return to work after
the tentative agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
The Teamsters and UPS late Monday agreed on a tentative
five-year contract providing substantial pension benefit increases
and 10,000 new full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
United States President Bill Clinton, vacationing outside
Washington D.C., told reporters the agreement that ended the
Teamsters' 15-day strike "is a victory for the proposition that
you can have good strong labor relations and treat your employees
well and make money in this economy of ours."
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman set up
residence at the Washington Hotel where the talks were held and
urged the sides to continue talking.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference at UPS headquarters in Atlanta earlier
today, UPS head, James Kelly, said UPS trucks and planes would be
up and running in a limited capacity tonight and in "full
operation" by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Teamsters spokesman Steve Trossman told reporters earlier today
that two-man teams from each local group representing UPS workers
have been summoned to Washington to vote today on the tentative
pact. If they approve the conditions of the new agreement, the
"rank-and-filers" will be told to report to their jobs while they
vote.
</P>
<P>
Teamsters President Ron Carey told reporters earlier today the
contract calls for wage increases of 3.10 dollars an hour for
full-time employees and 4.10 dollars an hour for part-timers over
the life of the contract, lifting full-time wages to 23 dollars an
hour and part-time to 15 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
