<HEADLINE> Serb Leaders Urged to Stop Infighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Parliament leader of Bosnia's
Serb Republic, Dragan Kalinic, today urged Bosnian Serb leaders to
stop infighting, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Serb Republic is facing a huge danger with the
intensification of infighting among the Serb leadership, Kalinic
said in a public rally in Doboj, about 100 kilometers north of
Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the Serbs could lose control of the strategic
town of Brcko in the coming elections if the infighting does not
come to a halt immediately.
</P>
<P>
Brcko, a northeastern town across the Sava River border with
Croatia, is vital for both Serbs and the Muslim-Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
For Serbs, the town sits astride a narrow corridor linking the
eastern and western halves of the Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
For the Muslim-Croat Federation, Brcko, with a river port, rail
depot and highway, provides the only trade link between Bosnia and
northern and western Europe.
</P>
<P>
Serbs and Muslims and Croats had fought heavily for the control
of the town during the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
Infighting among the Serb leadership flared up in early July.
</P>
<P>
Serb President Biljana Plavsic dissolved the parliament on July
3, but the decision was strongly opposed by parliament and the
Serb government believed to be actually controlled by former
president Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court ruled last week that Plavsic's
decision was unconstitutional and invalid. Plavsic rejected the
verdict of the court.
</P>
<P>
Among the wrangling of the Serb leadership, western countries
led by the United States voiced support for Plavsic and are trying
to force Karadzic out of the political arena and bring him to
trials before the International Criminal Tribunal for former
Yugoslavia in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic, who led Serbs in the Bosnian war, has been indicted
by the tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
