<HEADLINE> 30,000 Cambodian Refugees Flee into Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 Cambodian
refugees have fled into southeastern Thailand due to recent
attacks launched by Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen's
forces against those loyal to Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees, carrying possessions on bicycles,
motorcycles and carts, streamed into southeastern Thailand's Surin
province through Chong Chom pass in Dap Choeng district, local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities and non-government organizations were
providing food and medical services to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities Monday night opened the pass to let in
some 10,000 Cambodians, mainly women, children and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Another 20,000 Cambodians fled into Surin later as fighting
intensified near the Cambodian town of O'Smach, only several
kilometers away from the Thai-Cambodian border.
</P>
<P>
Major General Chirasak Prommopakorn, commander of Thailand's
Suranaree Task Force, said that the pass was opened to allow the
Cambodians to come in because they were in danger at O'Smach.
</P>
<P>
The refugees will be sent back once calmness was restored, the
commander said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some other sporadic groups of Cambodians fled into
other provinces in southeastern Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
