<HEADLINE> Russia's Auto Production Up First Time In the 1990s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Russia's auto production recorded
its first rise in the 1990s, with car, truck, bus and motorcycle
output increasing together in the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Russia rolled out 549,000 cars and 84,000 trucks, which was
12.9 percent and 11.5 percent more than the same period last
year. Bus and motorcycle production grew 16.8 percent and 79.7
percent to 24,800 and 35,000 respectively, the State Statistical
Committee said.
</P>
<P>
As Russia's two auto giants, Gorky and Volga, saw their
production going up steadily, Zil and Moskvich, which were on the
verge of shutdown last year, renewed operations this year with
production jumping 250 and 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
The recovery of Russia's auto industry was partly the result of
the government's campaign to ask public officials to use home
produced cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
