<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Death Toll Rises to 6 in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Death toll from heavy floods has
risen to six in the northern and central Philippines as of this
morning while thousands of residents are still combating rising
flood waters caused by continuous monsoon rains.
</P>
<P>
A civil defense officer at the National Disaster Coordinating
Council (NDCC) told Xinhua by telephone that as of 5:00 a.m.
today, six people have been confirmed dead and one injured in the
widespread flooding.
</P>
<P>
The six fatalities included four drowned, one buried by a
landslide, and the other electrocuted while walking in a flooded
street in Metro Manila, according to the latest NDCC report
provided by the officer.
</P>
<P>
But local press reports said eight were killed in flood-related
accidents during the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said thousands of residents in low-lying areas in
central Luzon and Visayas are still fighting the rising flood
waters which were brought about by heavy rains during the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 51,000 families or 264,000 persons have been
evacuated to makeshift shelter centers set up in churches or
public schools.
</P>
<P>
The worst-hit areas were Metro Manila or the national capital
region, and the provinces of Pampanga, Bataan and Bulacan in
central Luzon, according to the NDCC report.
</P>
<P>
In Metro Manila, more than 11,000 families or 67,000 people
were displaced Tuesday and transportation was paralyzed as about
80 percent of the capital area was submerged by flood waters.
</P>
<P>
Widespread flooding also forced the government to suspend
classes and services for one day in the capital region while many
business activities including trading at the stock and currency
markets were also canceled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But today, flood waters are seen subsiding in the capital city
and some streets are passable as heavy rains ceased to slash the
city late last night. Several highways linking Manila and nearby
provinces, however, remain impassable.
</P>
<P>
In central Luzon, the first alert level has been hoisted over
at least three main rivers around volcanic Mount Pinatub as heavy
rains loosened tons of volcanic ash on the mountain, turned them
into mud flows and swelled many rivers.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC report said troops, using amphibious vehicles, have
been dispatched to the stricken areas to help the rescue and
evacuation operations.
</P>
<P>
Weathermen forecast that monsoon rains will continue to batter
some parts of the country today after being intensified by Typhoon
Winnie which is now affecting Japan and China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
