<HEADLINE> Hungary, China to Strengthen Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian and Chinese
armies should maintain frequent contacts and further their
friendly ties, the Commander and Chief of the General Staff of the
Hungarian National Defense Forces, Vegh Ferenc, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Vegh made the remark at a meeting with the visiting Deputy
Director of the Chinese General Political Department, Zhou Ziyu,
who arrived in Budapest last Friday heading a delegation on a
six-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Vegh said China has been and will remain an important component
of the global strategy.
</P>
<P>
He was also fully confident of the complete success of his
China tour early September, believing the visit would certainly
boost the development of relations between the Hungarian and
Chinese armies.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy State Secretary of the Hungarian Ministry of
Defense, Gyarmati Istvan, also met the delegation.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that both the Hungarian and Chinese governments
were playing active roles in maintaining regional and world peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
The differences between the two countries in certain fields
would not affect the relationship between the two nations,
Gyarmati noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hungary's entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), Gyarmati said the entry would not weaken
Hungary's links with non-NATO countries, but further strengthen
them instead.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his appreciation of China's understanding of
Hungary's entry into NATO.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the Chinese army is willing to strengthen the
friendly cooperation with the Hungarian army on the principles of
mutual respect, equality, mutual benefit, and seeking common
ground while reserving differences and common development.
</P>
<P>
The delegation ends its visit tomorrow. 
