<HEADLINE> Armenia Supports China on Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YEREVAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Armenia strongly supports
China's position on the Taiwan issue and opposes Taiwan
authorities' attempts to join the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Aleksandr Arzumanyan, the Armenian Minister of Foreign Affairs,
reiterated this today to Chinese National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee Vice-Chairman Wang Bingqian who heads a
visiting delegation here.
</P>
<P>
He said Armenia would never develop any official ties with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-Armenian relations, Arzumanyan said Armenia attached
great importance to developing ties with China. The joint
declaration signed by Armenian President Levon Ter-Petroscyan and
Chinese leaders in Beijing last year was of great significance to
the future development of bilateral ties. The two countries should
make joint efforts to further close links with each other, the
Minister added.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that although China and Armenia are far from each
other in distance, the two peoples have a long history of friendly
ties. This friendship had been strengthened and improved since the
two countries established diplomatic relations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
China was also glad to see stable bilateral political ties and
broader cooperation in areas such as science and trade.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government highly appraised Armenia's consistent
position on the Taiwan issue and the no official ties with Taiwan
policy on this matter. China hopes to gain further supports from
the Armenian government in the future, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Arzumanyan congratulated China on its resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong and said China's experience
on solving the Hong Kong issue was of referential significance to
Armenia.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of the Armenian National Assembly, the
Chinese delegation arrived in Armenia on Monday on an official
goodwill visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
