<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka Takes Effective Measures to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
taken effective measures to promote tourism which shows prospects
of resilience this year.
</P>
<P>
By July, tourist arrivals had reached 205,101, an increase of
20.6 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Tourism Board sources, the government has
recognized tourism's essential contribution to economic and social
development of the country and adopted many new measures to boost
tourism in the past year.
</P>
<P>
It initiated an image building campaign at a cost of 2.5
million U.S. dollars in 16 selected countries to establish that
Sri Lanka is a safe destination for tourists and a safe place for
investment.
</P>
<P>
A hotel school with modern facilities at a cost of 2.8 million
U.S. dollars is under construction to train human resources for
the industry.
</P>
<P>
The government has also approved the plan to set up a National
Art and Cultural Center in Colombo. This project is to facilitate
entertainment and the sale of local handicrafts to tourists. It
will endeavor to boost Sri Lanka's art and culture too.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, a Sri Lanka pavilion will be set up at the
permanent exhibition center at the Commonwealth Institute, London.
It is planned to reach a wider audience and promote Sri Lanka to
tourists and students specially from commonwealth countries,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The construction of 329 new hotels with 22,570 rooms has been
approved by the government.
</P>
<P>
The turnover tax on the tourist industry has been removed and a
Tourist Promotion Authority to encourage private sector
participation will soon be established. Duty-free and turnover tax
concessions are to be offered for refreshments at hotels.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 59.3 million US dollars has been invested by the
government in other tourism projects such as golf courses and
entertainment, according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Under a tourism master plan (1992-2001), Sri Lanka will attract
875,000 tourists by the year 2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
