<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Sets Ceiling for Borrowing from IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has set a
ceiling of 20 billion U.S. dollars for Thailand to borrow from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and foreign countries and
institutions to help revive its economy.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Cabinet endorsed the ceiling at its weekly meeting
Tuesday when it heard reports from the Finance Ministry on the
result of negotiations between Thailand and the IMF, according to
a press release from the Thai Government House today.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet instructed all the public and private agencies
concerned to join hands in implementing the action plans concerned
to achieve the goal agreed between the Thai government and the IMF
in due course.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Finance Ministry and the Central Bank also were
instructed to expedite the financial reform plan, strengthen
supervision over the financial institutions, establish the deposit
guarantee institution, and control the budget spending under the
target amount and time frame agreed by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Among the decisions of the Cabinet meeting Tuesday, Thailand's
Eighth National Economic and Social Development Plan (1997-2001)
will be readjusted to meet the macro economic goal agreed by the
IMF, including tightening investment plans by the state
enterprises and expediting privatization.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will work together with the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank to formulate an action plan to revive and promote
Thailand's industrial exports.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Thai Cabinet also instructed the related
government departments to work together to improve the country's
work on micro and macro economic statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
