<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Court Orders Release Of Former Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Supreme Court
Tuesday ordered the release of Sirisena Cooray, a minister in the
former United National Party government, who was detained for
allegedly conspiring an assassination plot against President
Chandrika Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court declared that the fundamental rights of
Cooray had been violated and that his arrest and detention were
"illegal," local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered that Cooray be paid 200,000 rupees
(about 3,400 U.S. dollars) as compensation and costs.
</P>
<P>
Cooray, who was detained under the Public Security Act on June
16 and had not since been brought before a magistrate, filed a
fundamental rights application through Attorney-at-Law Sunil K.
Rodrigo.
</P>
<P>
Cooray's detention, ordered by Secretary of Defense
Chandrananda de Silva on representations from the police, was
executed without convincing grounds, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Cooray returned to the country in April this year after staying
abroad for more than one year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
