<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Farmers go on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan farmers went on a
national strike today, accusing the government of lacking a
consistent public policy on agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Farmers claimed the inconsistent policy on agriculture is
provoking a shortage of food, and a lack of Venezuelan products
available for international markets.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural producers and Cattle breeders' unions from all
over the country decided to rally next Thursday in Cabello Port,in
the northern state of Carabobo.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the president of National Federation of
Farmers (Fedeagro) and the president of National Federation of
Cattle Breeders (Fedenaga) presented a document to the Finance
Ministry, expressing their demands.
</P>
<P>
The document stressed that the farmers faced market handicaps
as well as action by armed groups not only on the border with
Colombia but in Venezuela itself.
</P>
<P>
They also asked the Ministry to limit imports and pave the way
for national products to enter domestic markets.
</P>
<P>
They demanded Congress make an emergency agricultural law since
agriculture and cattle were strategic activities for the nation.
</P>
<P>
Today's strike is supported by several political parties, as
well as governors and majors from 14 states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
