<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Leaders Reject Referendum on EMU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Federal Chancellor
Viktor Klima and Vice Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel rejected today
any referendum on Austria's membership in the Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Klima and Schuessel took their stand at a press conference here
after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Austrian main opposition Freedom Party today officially
submitted a petition to the interior ministry for a referendum on
Austria's EMU membership.
</P>
<P>
Klima, who chairs the Social Democratic Party, said, he "firmly
believes Austria should be admitted to the EMU in the first
group," and opposed any kind of "wavering" on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Austria has made great efforts for the EMU
membership in the past two years, he added, "If we abandon the
plan now, that will not be logical."
</P>
<P>
He further stressed that it will be "unthinkable", and even
seriously harmful to its national economy and stability, if
Austria fails to join the EMU while Germany does.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel, also minister of foreign affairs, said the Austrian
government already sounded the public opinion when joining the
European Union. "Any move that creates doubt and distrust will
harm the country's economy, job opportunities and competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
The EMU will be kicked off on January 1, 1999, as scheduled in
the Maastricht Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
