<HEADLINE> China Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The frontpage of the leading newspaper carried an article on
the efforts made by governments in east China's coastal areas to
establish a good market order while creating a socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
-- The Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the
State Council showed great concern about Shanghai and Zhejiang and
Fujian provinces, which were hit by "Typhoon Winnie" on
Monday. President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng both sent
greetings to officials, people and People's Liberation Army
soldiers in these regions fighting against the typhoon disaster.
</P>
<P>
-- A feature story gave an introduction to the deeds of Hou
Dianlu, a model judicial assistant in a remote township in
northwest China's Gansu Province. Hou devoted his life to
maintaining peace and unity among the residents of his township
and solved numerous civil disputes.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage story described the progress Shanghai has made
in different economic sectors since the 14th National Congress of
the CPC due to the improved economic structures.
</P>
<P>
-- Participants in a Beijing forum, jointly organized by the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation and the
Propaganda Department of the CPC Central Committee yesterday,
agreed that China's opening-up drive has entered a new historical
stage since the 14th National Congress of the CPC in 1992.
</P>
<P>
-- The economic returns of China's industrial sector,
especially those of the state-owned enterprises, continued to
improve in the first half of this year, according to a report
released by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's national economy grew steadily in July, with the
value of the industrial output of enterprises above township level
reaching 162.5 billion yuan (19.6 billion US dollars) in July, up
8.4 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Typhoon Winnie, the most violent to hit China in a decade,
caused a death toll of at least 19 people in Zhejiang yesterday
after killing 25 earlier in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese Government yesterday expressed serious concern
at recent remarks by a senior Japanese official relating to the
scope of Japan-US security co-operation.
</P>
<P>
On August 17, Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama
indicated in an Asahi TV interview that the "surrounding areas"
covered by Japan-US security collaboration should "naturally
include the Taiwan Straits." 
</P>
