<HEADLINE> Chinese Gymnasts to Compete in Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Reigning Olympic men's
individual all-around champion Li Xiaoshuang will miss the World
Gymnastics Championships slated from August 31 to September 7 at
Lausanne, Switzerland, the Chinese Gymnastics Association revealt
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old defending world champion hasn't been in
competitive action since he suffered an ankle injury during
practice this March.
</P>
<P>
Li's absence is considered as a major blow to the Chinese men's
team, which has been depleted by the retirement of four key
figures -- Li Jing, Li Dashuang, Huang Liping and Huang Huadong --
accountable for the 1995 Worlds' team title.
</P>
<P>
Li's teammate, another first choice gymnast for the team event,
Fan Hongbin, provided another noticable absentee as he is now
competing in Sicily for the World University Games.
</P>
<P>
The main aim for China in the Championships, officials said,
was to take it as an opportunity to hone skills for the 2000
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese men and women's gymnasts, setting off here today,
will first travel to the Swiss capital Bern for a triangular
challenge competitions with Belarus and the host country
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The Championships, taking place on a biannual base, features
around 550 gymnasts from 66 gymnastics associations.
</P>
<P>
Following is the namelist of the Chinese gymnasts for the
World Championships:
</P>
<P>
Men's:
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinjing, Shen Jian, Lu Yufu, Huang Xu, Fan Bin, Xiao
Junfeng, Li Xiaopeng
</P>
<P>
Women's:
</P>
<P>
Mo Huilan, Liu Xuan, Kui Yuanyuan, Meng Fei, Ji Liya, Bi
Wenjing, Zhou Duan
</P>
</TEXT>
