<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Oil Export in Down Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Oil export has been Ecuador's
number one foreign currency generator for a quarter of century,
but its role may be soon replaced by traditional products,
according to the Institute on Studies for Development today.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's export would undergo an utter change by the year
2000, when oil sales would account for 30 percent of the total
while traditional products -- bananas and sea products -- will go
up to 40 percent, the institute says.
</P>
<P>
Within the year, experts predict, banana export would rise to
1.2 billion dollars, sea products between 1.1 or 1.2 billion
dollars, while oil to 1.29 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
