<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China's Guangdong Province Restricts Noise Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- New regulations on the
restriction of noise pollution will go into effect later this year
in Guangdong, an economically-developed province in south China.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that firms and vehicles that
create too much noise in residential areas will be punished,
according to the Guangdong Provincial Regulations on the
Prevention of Noise Pollution, which are expected to be passed by
the Provincial People's Congress next month.
</P>
<P>
The use of steam machines for driving piles and concrete mixers
will be forbidden in downtown areas. Without permission, building
sites in cities will have to stop construction at night.
</P>
<P>
Noise levels at entertainment places will also be limited in
the evenings.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises and individuals who break the regulations will be
fined 200 yuan (24 US dollars) to 100,000 yuan (12,048 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Due to rapid economic growth, noise, air and water pollution
has become much worse in the province. Its capital city of
Guangzhou, Foshan and Yunfu have became the most seriously
polluted cities in the Pearl River Delta, which borders Hong Kong
and Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
