<HEADLINE> Indonesia Draws Up Foreign Relations Bill: Alatas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Foreign Ministry has
drawn up a bill on foreign relations to enable its foreign policy
to be executed in more integrated and coordinated ways, Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
In his address at a function here to observe his ministry's
52nd anniversary Tuesday, Alatas said diplomacy in today's world
cannot be pursued in partial or sectorally compartmentalized ways.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not give details of the bill.
</P>
<P>
"We can't conduct diplomacy if it is fragmentized into separate
departments such as political, economic, socio-cultural,
information, defense and security etc. It must be carried out in
integrated and well-coordinated ways," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said Indonesia had made a series of international
efforts to spearhead the establishment of a new order in
international relations, namely, the holding of the Afro-Asian
conference, the founding of the Non-Aligned Movement and ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations).
</P>
<P>
He said the 21st century would be the third millennium which
was often said to be the century of global competition.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Indonesian diplomats should face the challenges of
the future with professionalism, fighting spirit and high
morality, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
