<HEADLINE> Educators Criticize New Electronic Pets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The electronic pets craze sweeping
through many Asian countries is meeting strong criticism from
Chinese educators, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"It is naive to expect children to develop loving hearts simply
by playing with a toy. It will come and go as any passing fad,"
said Ai Ling, vice-chairman of the National Committee of Chinese
Yong Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Beijing has seen a rise in pet sales in
big stores since late May, but sales have dropped since late July.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from more sellers, media's voice and teachers words have
contributed to this." said Sun Zhenpo, a manager with the
Wangfujing Department Store in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, stories and comments, most of which are
negative towards the pets, are frequently seen in newspapers, and
the State Education Commission (Sec) has also urged teachers to
give more lessons on how to spend money.
</P>
<P>
Fu Guoliang, deputy director of Sec's Primary Education
Department, warned children against becoming too involved in the
emotional world created by electronic pets.
</P>
<P>
Ai said the toy is not as instructive as advertisements
describe. The machine is personified and caters to children's
craving to make friends in an increasingly busy world.
</P>
<P>
But it is dangerous to have communications with friends in the
real world replaced by raising the electronic animals. They are
the same as game machines, which become harmful if children become
too absorbed in them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Raises Interest Rates to Stabilize Rupiah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian monetary authorities
Tuesday raised interest rates sharply in an attempt to save the
rupiah from continued slide, a Bank Indonesia (BI) official said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its one-week rates on Bank Indonesia
Certificates to 20 percent from 10.5 percent, head of the bank's
Money Market Division Suprijo Martono said here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Two-week rates were raised to 22 percent from 11 percent,
one-month rates to 30 percent from 11.625 percent, and three-month
rates to 28 percent from 11.5 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rates were left unchanged on overnight certificates at 15
percent, six-day certificates at 16 percent, six-month
certificates at 12.125 percent and one-year certificates at 12.750
percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah weakened against the U.S. dollar after the central
bank scrapped its intervention band last Thursday. The rupiah
dipped to a new low of 3,010 rupiah to the dollar Monday.
</P>
<P>
As a result of BI's measure, the value of the U.S. dollar
remained at the 2,915/2,925 rupiah level in inter-bank
transactions in the spot market Tuesday, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Stock Exchange's composite index fell 1.5 percent
with the announcement that interest rates had been raised,
reversing morning attempts by the government to support the
market.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economic and Financial Affairs Saleh
Afiff said Tuesday that the government will continue exercising
its current tight money policy through fiscal and monetary means
in an effort to stabilize the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
He said what was important was the stability of macro-economy.
</P>
<P>
"It would be all right if the drop did occur -- possibly at
only 0.2 or 0.3 percent -- so long as macro-economic stability
maintained," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's economy grows by an average of 7.9 percent a year
during the first three years of the current five-year development
plan period (1994-1999).
</P>
<P>
Last year, the growth was recorded at 7.98 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
