<HEADLINE> Guangdong's Exports Up 33 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Exports from south China's
Guangdong Province surged 33 percent in the first seven months of
this year from the same period in 1996, according to Vice-Governor
Tang Bingquan.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that exports came to 39.3 billion US dollars during
that period.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was confidant that the province would meet its
target of exporting 65 billion dollars worth of exports this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that if imports and exports grow at an annual rate of
10 to 12 percent, Guangdong's foreign trade volume in 2000 will
hit 140 billion dollars, 80 billion dollars of which will come
from exports.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign trade volume in 2010 is expected to reach 460
billion dollars, of which 240 billion dollars will come from
exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Tang, Guangdong accounts for 40 percent of China's
imports and exports. Moreover, exports contribute about 40 percent
of Guangdong's gross domestic product -- the value of goods and
services produced.
</P>
<P>
He called for greater efforts to align Guangdong's foreign
trade management system with the international practices, and
improve the competitive edge of local traders and the quality of
export commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
