<HEADLINE> World's Top Teams to Compete in 4-Man Beach Volleyball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The world's top 12 volleyball
teams are to compete in the four-day Kent Beach Volleyball 4-Men
Grand Slam starting in the Victoria Park here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They are joined here by teams from China, Iran, India,
Australia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, United States, Australia and New Zealand are seeded
teams.
</P>
<P>
In an official draw held Tuesday afternoon for the preliminary
round, the teams were pooled into four groups of three, with world
number one Brazil to play Mexico and Iran in Group A.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champions from last year's Atlanta Games the United
States were pooled into Group B with China and India.
</P>
<P>
In Group C are Australia, Hong Kong, China and South Africa
while New Zealand, Japan and Indonesia are in Group D.
</P>
<P>
The top eight teams from the round-robin preliminary round will
go through to the Cup competition in two round-robin groups of
four teams each.
</P>
<P>
The bottom four will play in two round-robin groups of two in
the Plate competition. The top two teams of each group in the Cup
will go through to the semi-finals on a cross system with the
winners going to meet in the final, which is slated for Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, winners of last year's event here, are to take the
challenge from the Americans, who lost in the 1996 final here.
</P>
<P>
The United States had a chance for a team training only after
their arrival here earlier this week. With Mark Presho the only
player from the Olympic Games though, the U.S. team has a fairly
good chance to win this year, said the team's coach Scott Sato.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong hosted the inaugural beach volleyball tournament in
1990, followed by events in 1991, 1992 and 1995, all being two-men
tournament.
</P>
<P>
From last year on, the event has taken four-men format. This
year's is the sixth in the annual series.
</P>
<P>
Iran, Mexico, New Zealand and India are making their tournament
debut here this year. 
</P>
