<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Establishment of Foreign-Funded TV, Radio Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's
highest administrative body, has issued new regulations on the
management of TV and radio stations, banning foreigners from
investing in this sector in any form.
</P>
<P>
The 55-article regulations deal with the establishment of
Chinese TV and radio stations, and the language and content to be
included in programs and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
TV and radio stations must be established by the radio and
television department of the government at and above the county
level, according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
The regulations state that no other units or individuals may
set up a TV or a radio station. The government prohibits the
establishment of TV and radio stations in such forms as wholly
foreign-owned enterprises, Sino-foreign joint ventures or
Sino-foreign cooperative businesses.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, signed by Premier Li Peng, will go into effect
on September 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
