The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian federal government yesterday blocked
Australia's first heroin trial in the country's capital Canberra,
because a trial supplying heroin to drug addicts "would be sending
the wrong signal" about illicit drugs to young people.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Alleged Nazi war criminal Konrad Kalejs, who was ordered
deported by both the United States and Canada, will walk free in
Sydney this morning after Canadian authorities gave him just four
hours to pack his bags and leave the country. The 84-year-old man,
who emigrated to Australia in 1950, allegedly served as a
lieutenant with a concentration camp in Latvia during 1941-1944
where more than 20,000 Jews are thought to have perished.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The Reserve Bank of Australia is no longer certain that the
economy is set to pick up in coming months. In a cautious
statement yesterday, it again forecast an acceleration of growth
this financial year, but conceded that this might not arrive.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- John Prescott, chief executive of Australia's biggest
company BHP, said any of the mining giant's assets will either be
restructured or sold unless they will earn a return on their
capital of more than 10 percent by May 1998.  
