<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Recoup More Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Technology stocks led a broad
rally on Wall Street today, wiping almost every remaining trace of
Friday's selloff, as the Federal Reserve decided not to raise
interest rates to quench inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, which on Monday recouped a
little less than half of Friday's 247-point drop, jumped 114.74
points to 7,918.10.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 545.58
million shares as against 514.27 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also posted sizable gains, led by the
technology-rich Nasdaq composite index, which rose 2 percent on
the day.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index bounced 31.19 points to 1,600.71.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 13.52 points to
926.01, and the NYSE composite index rose 5.99 to 479.54. and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.63 to 641.22.
</P>
<P>
Although the market's recent tumble came amid worries that
inflationary pressures may be mounting again, there is no
expectation in the market that the Federal Reserve will take any
action today to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
In another sign that the economic pace may still be moderate
enough to keep inflation in check without higher Fed rates, the
Commerce Department reported this morning that housing starts were
unchanged in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
