<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berlin to Mark Return of Jewish War Refugees From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A commemorative plaque will be
unveiled in Berlin Thursday to mark the 50th anniversary of the
return of 295 Jewish refugees to Germany from their second
hometown, Shanghai, after the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made today by the German association
"Active Museum Fascism and Resistance" in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese port city of Shanghai gave shelter to about 18,000
Jews, mainly from Germany and Austria, who fled the holocaust
during the Nazi era. Only a very small proportion of the Jewish
refugees returned to Germany after the war. Most of them migrated
to Israel, the United States and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the war-time refugees will participate in an
unveiling ceremony for the commemorative plaque Thursday in
Berlin. A symposium titled "The End of Exile in Shanghai" and an
exhibition are also scheduled for the next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970820.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fire Deaths Highest in Six Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Fires engulfed 4,990 people
last year in the United States, more than at any time since 1990,
the National Fire Protection Association said.
</P>
<P>
"This is certainly disappointing news, but we're hopeful it
doesn't signal a long-term trend," The Associated Press quoted
association spokesman John Hall as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hall said fire death rates have generally declined throughout
this century. There were about 6,000 deaths a year for most of the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Now we seem to be locked into roughly 4,700 deaths a year," he
said. "Whatever else is true, the numbers demonstrate that fire
still poses a significant problem in the U.S."
</P>
<P>
Eighty-one percent of fire fatalities were in homes, the
association said Monday. Fire departments responded to the same
number of fires in 1996 as in 1995 -- nearly 2 million.
</P>
<P>
However, arson fires declined by 5.5 percent. Injuries from
fires remained about the same. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
